<DIV1 TYPE="prologue">
<PB REF="3">
<HEAD>PROLOGUE.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">Spoken by Mr. LEWES, in the Character of an "OLD WOMAN."</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDWARD TOPHAM, E&s;q.</BYLINE>
<LG>
<L>START not, good folks!&mdash;I'm only come a wooing&mdash;</L>
<L>You know the fair &s;ex ever will be doing&mdash;</L>
<L>In <HI>Moliere</HI>'s days the practice was mo&s;t common</L>
<L>For men to tru&s;t their works to &s;ome old woman,</L>
<L>Who&s;e matron coun&s;el, and approving choice,</L>
<L>Secur'd their favourite bard the public voice.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Will this bright circle then, who round me &s;it,</L>
<L>Deny my power of giving weight to wit?</L>
<L>Is there a gallant &s;wain who dares repine,</L>
<L>Struck by the lu&s;tre of an eye like mine?</L>
<L>Oh! no&mdash;thank Heav'n! the baby-rage is pa&s;t,</L>
<L>And elder ladies captivate at la&s;t:</L>
<L>The full-blown dame, who rules o'er ton and ta&s;te,</L>
<L>With rouge for ro&s;es, and for lilies pa&s;te,</L>
<L>Now reigns the <HI>Ovid</HI> of a new-made &s;chool,</L>
<L>To teach young gentlemen&mdash;to play the fool.</L>
<L>If in the tender pa&s;&s;ion then <HI>we</HI> &s;hine,</L>
<L>And age can give us <HI>"&s;macks"</HI> as well as wine,</L>
<L>No wonder that the fa&s;hion is becoming,</L>
<L>And Church, Law, Politics, have their old women.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Our Bard to-night, all anxious for his fate,</L>
<L>Begg'd the indulgence of a t&ecirc;te-&agrave;-t&ecirc;te:</L>
<L>Fir&s;t I was coy&mdash;but women will give way&mdash;</L>
<L>He &s;aw me tender, and produc'd his Play&mdash;</L>
<L>Reque&s;ted I would make his ca&s;e my own,</L>
<L>And plead a de&s;perate cau&s;e before the town.</L>
<L>&mdash;Well then,&mdash;to &s;peak at once my real mind&mdash;</L>
<L>For, on my virtue, I can't be unkind,</L>
<L>Save &s;ome old jokes which now and then appear,</L>
<L>And drop in Parliament, as well as here,</L>
<L>I tru&s;t this Hou&s;e will take the Trea&s;ury &s;ide,</L>
<L>Let the debates go on, and not divid$.</L>
<L><PB REF="4">
But as the Scenic Si&s;ters long have varied,</L>
<L>And as we wi&s;h our mea&s;ures may be carried,</L>
<L>To &s;top the mouths of critic oppo&s;ition,</L>
<L>We form a tragi-comic coalition:</L>
<L>Water and wine&mdash;a beverage half and half&mdash;</L>
<L>Broad Humour ju&s;t peeps in to make you laugh;</L>
<L>While intermix'd the tender &s;cenes appear,</L>
<L>To draw from Beauty's eye Compa&s;&s;ion's tear.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Such is our Author's plan&mdash;if trite or common,</L>
<L>Condemn me as a doating, fal&s;e Old Woman!</L>
<L>&mdash;But mark, the critic who approves <HI>my</HI> bard,</L>
<L>May claim a <HI>"cha&s;te &s;alute"</HI> as his reward.</L>
</LG>
