<DIV1>
<PB REF="5">
<HEAD>THE REPARATION.</HEAD>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>ACT I.</HEAD>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">An Av$nue leading to <HI>LORD HECTIC'S</HI> Hou&s;e.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> BELCOUR <HI>and</HI> LOVELESS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BELCOUR.</SPEAKER>
<P>COME, come, my dear Lovele&s;s, don't be too rigid; you mu&s;t pardon the extravagances of a lover.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>With all my heart, if they are not carried too far&mdash;but I wou'd not have you let your imagination run away with your rea&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Impo&s;&s;ible, my friend&mdash;No imagination can do her ju&s;tice; I tell you, my Harriet is the charminge&s;t girl, the mo&s;t enchanting creature upon earth: <Q>&startq;a per|&s;on endow'd with every grace, and a mind enrich'd with every virtue.&endq;</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>In that ca&s;e, my dear Belcour, don't trifle with your happine&s;s&mdash;Marry her immediately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Marry her!&mdash;That wou'd be trifling with my happine&s;s indeed&mdash;Why, you forget &s;he is the daugh|ter of our whim&s;ical neighbour here, Sir Gregory
<PB N="2" REF="6">
Glovetop, knighted by the old court for a forty ye$rs at|tendance upon it in the humble quality of gentleman|u&s;her, and di&s;mi&s;s'd in the late reform, without any fortune but his &s;tiff-topp'd gloves, and remains of a tat|ter'd wardrobe: think what a charming patrimony I &s;hou'd be heir to&mdash;a &s;hort &s;word, and a dre&s;s'd coat with a hoop in it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, my gay, lively friend, let me entreat you, act like a man of honour. Con&s;ider the &s;en&s;ibility of an innocent mind; nor &s;port with the heart you cannot properly make your own.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, Lovele&s;s, now you are too &s;erious. Is there any violent harm in u&s;ing a little art to give a woman an opportunity of quieting her con&s;cience, and gratifying, without the ceremonies, your inclination as well as her own?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(agitated)</STAGE> Pray excu&s;e me&mdash;I am the la&s;t man on earth you &s;hou'd con&s;ult on &s;uch a &s;ubject.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, come, this gravity does not &s;it well upon a man whom I have known the foremo&s;t in a fro|lic, and the fir&s;t advi&s;er of mi&s;chief&mdash;I expect your a&s;&s;i&s;tance in the bu&s;ine&s;s.&mdash;Say, &s;hall I fairly take her off? or, if you think it better&mdash;&s;uppo&s;e I pretend to marry her, and &s;o&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(more agitated)</STAGE> I beg you will urge me no further on this head&mdash;Indeed I am very unfit to give an opinion: your conver&s;ation probably may affect me more than you imagine&mdash;but let us call another topic.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, I hope the name of marriage has not frighten'd you, becau&s;e you have ju&s;t got rid of the rea|lity&mdash;Every body knows the terms you liv'd upon with Lady Su&s;an; but it was a match of your father's mak|ing, and, as Heaven has kindly releas'd you from it, why the &s;ooner you forget her the better. So pr'ythee now drop your heroics, and (as you once had a turn for in|trigue)
<PB N="3" REF="7">
put me in a way of obtaining my mi&s;tre&s;s; for have her I mu&s;t, co&s;t what it will.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, my friend, remember&mdash;If you &s;hou'd proceed, and &s;acrifice to a momentary inclination the rectitude of your heart, you will be as mi&s;erable as I am, and live to lament crimes you never can recall.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Lovele&s;s, explain your&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Know then, before my marriage with Lady Su&s;an, I was attach'd&mdash;tenderly attach'd, to the mo&s;t lovely of her &s;ex, the daughter of a gentleman who had &s;erv'd his country with bravery and honour&mdash;but had retir'd on half pay, to a &s;mall neat dwelling near my father's park; where, wholly devoted to the education of his darling child, his only wi&s;h was to train her up in the paths of virtue&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>You affect me exceedingly&mdash;pray go on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>The vicinity of our abodes gave me frequent opportunities of tracing the &s;en&s;ibility of Julia's mind, <Q>&startq;and winning the affections of her virgin heart. Notwith|&s;tanding the humblene&s;s of her fortune, I &s;hou'd un|doubtedly have married her, had I not too well known the ambitious views and rigid temper of my father.&mdash;Tran&s;ported however with her blooming charms, which were daily heighten'd in my eyes by proofs of growing tenderne&s;s, incapable of exi&s;ting without her;&endq;</Q>&mdash;and, too con&s;cious of her purity to expect to gain her by other means, I was ba&s;e enough to li&s;ten to the &s;pecious arguments of libertine friends, and engaged in a plan to deceive her by a pretended marriage&mdash;I &s;ee you are &s;hock'd at my villainy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray proceed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>My family at length obl$ging me to unite my&s;elf with Lady Su&s;an, I was compell'd to reveal the fatal &s;ecret.&mdash;O, Belcour! picture to your&s;elf the di&s;tre&s;s of an unhappy woman, bereft of that honour, the only
<PB N="4" REF="8">
portion which her father's narrow fortune cou'd be&s;tow, by the very man in whom &s;he had plac'd unbounded confidence&mdash;<HI>(bur&s;ts into tears)</HI> 'tis impo&s;&s;ible to de&s;cribe the conflict in her bo&s;om. In vain I tried every argu|ment I cou'd &s;ugge&s;t to tranquillize her mind.&mdash;She treated my profe&s;&s;ions of undimini&s;h'd regard with ap|parent coldne&s;s and di&s;dain; and, together with our infant &s;on, left the hou&s;e where &s;he re&s;ided; eluded every re|&s;earch I cou'd make; and at length, I have every rea&s;on to believe, fell a victim to my treachery and ingratitude.</P>
</SP>
<Q>&startq;&endq;

<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope not&mdash;Come, come, my friend, your apprehen&s;ions may be groundle&s;s&mdash;She may yet live to &s;oothe and cheri&s;h your repentant hours&mdash;at lea&s;t your child may want a parent&mdash;Why then think of leaving a country where it is your duty to &s;tay?&mdash;that if the unfortunate mother is no more, you may call down forgivene&s;s from her relenting &s;pirit, by encreas'd affection to her blamele&s;s &s;on.</P>
</SP></Q>
<Q>&startq;&endq;

<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas! that con&s;olation is denied me. He too, poor innocent, hath &s;har'd his mother's &s;orrows, and her fate. Notwith&s;tanding my &s;tricte&s;t enquiry, I have not been able to gain any tidings of either of them; my only &s;ucce&s;s has been in di&s;covering the re|treat of Julia's di&s;con&s;olate father.</P>
</SP></Q>
<Q>&startq;&endq;

<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>But &s;ay, how did he &s;u&s;tain &s;o rude a &s;hock?</P>
</SP></Q>
<Q>&startq;

<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! imagining that &s;he was privy to the impo&s;ition of the marriage, he turn'd that rage again&s;t his daughter which ought only to have fallen on me, and imprecated &s;evere&s;t cur&s;es upon him&s;elf if ever he &s;aw her again.</P>
</SP>
&endq;</Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>I pity your &s;ituation, Lovele&s;s: <Q>&startq;but re|collect, that your conduct, tho' criminal, was the re&s;ult rather of your father's di&s;po&s;ition than your own.&endq;</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lov$le&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q>&startq;No, my friend, I have &s;earch'd every ave|nue
<PB N="5" REF="9">
to my heart, and find no hope of con&s;olation.&endq;</Q>&mdash;I have however written to the injur'd veteran: confe&s;s'd the pretences under which his daughter was deceiv'd, and offer'd the only atonement in my power, the entire di&s;po|&s;al of my fortune, as he &s;hall think proper.&mdash;I &s;hall wait his an&s;wer here; and then bid adieu to a country em|bitter'd to me by the &s;evere&s;t of pangs&mdash;the &s;ad remem|brance of a di&s;graceful triumph over un&s;u&s;pecting inno|cence and tendere&s;t love.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>A truce to the&s;e melancholy ideas&mdash;<Q>&startq;let us, like friends, be u&s;eful to each other.&endq;</Q> You &s;hall pro|fit by my advice, and I by your misfortunes.&mdash;<Q>&startq;I will de&s;i&s;t from every di&s;honourable plan again&s;t Harriet; and you &s;hall learn, from my philo&s;ophy, to conquer griefs which cannot now avail.&endq;</Q> You &s;hall &s;tay with us this &s;ummer, and &s;hare the rural recreations of this charming &s;eat&mdash;Our noble ho&s;t, my Lord Hectic, will do all in his power to entertain you; and indeed it is im|po&s;&s;ible to re&s;train the &s;mile at &s;eeing him con&s;tantly la|bouring to become the very character you lament&mdash;an anxious wi&s;h to be thought a libertine, without con&s;titu|tion, or even inclination, to be really &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ab&s;urd man! Yet how happy I &s;hou'd think my&s;elf, had my de&s;ires never carry'd me further!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let me however caution you again&s;t&punc; his &s;i&s;ter, Lady Betty Wormwood, who, without half his good qualities, has a much more mi&s;chievous di&s;po&s;ition. She does all &s;he can to keep her brother &s;ingle, expecting to inherit great part of his fortune, and therefore charitably abu&s;es every woman &s;he hears of. My good aunt too, Mi&s;s Penelope Zodiac, her gue&s;t and companion, tho' &s;he is generally in the clouds, now and then conde&s;cends to favour us with &s;ome earthly ideas, on purpo&s;e to join in the invectives again&s;t her own &s;ex, with all that benignity
<PB N="6" REF="10">
of di&s;po&s;ition for which old maids are &s;o remarkably&punc; famous.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>O &s;pare your aunt, at lea&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not I&mdash;I only follow her example&mdash;She &s;pares nobody.&mdash;But let us adjourn to the man&s;ion; my Lord has by this time, I dare &s;ay, fini&s;h'd his morning's ride on his chamber-hor&s;e; in which ca&s;e his Iri&s;h cou&s;in, Captain Swagger, <Q>&startq;who has nothing good about him but his appetite,&endq;</Q> will be bawling for his breakfa&s;t.&mdash;The Captain is very unlike his countrymen; for they are generally brave to an extreme&mdash;but he, I believe, is not &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(in a pen&s;ive manner)</STAGE> I am &s;orry for it&mdash;An Iri&s;hman without courage is very rarely to be met with; &s;o that the novelty of it will &s;urprize me at lea&s;t&mdash;tho' nothing, I fear, can give me entertainment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(taking his arm)</STAGE> Come, come, my friend, di&s;&s;ipate the&s;e gloomy thoughts, and endeavour to be, what once you were, the life and ornament of &s;ociety.</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt familiarly.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">A dre&s;&s;ing-room in <HI>LORD HECTIC'S</HI> hou&s;e. He in a robe|de-chambre. <HI>CAPTAIN SWAGGER</HI> dre&s;s'd in an old uniform, long ba&s;ket-hilted &s;word. My Lord &s;eated on a chamber-hor&s;e, &amp;c.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is the way, Captain Swagger, to get air and exerci&s;e at one's lei&s;ure, by letters patent, like a gentleman; without being oblig'd to leave one's own chamber, and &s;cour acro&s;s the country for it, like a po&s;t-boy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger&punc;</SPEAKER>
<P>True, my Lord&mdash;and, by my &s;houl, the hor&s;e won't be ea&s;ily knock'd up.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="7" REF="11">
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(getting off)</STAGE> There, there&mdash;I have taken a pretty long ride to-day. <STAGE>(coming forward)</STAGE> What a fine thing it is to be hale and hearty! <STAGE>(coughing)</STAGE> one gets thro' &s;o much fatigue without minding it; and looks as fre&s;h as a ro&s;e after all <STAGE>(coughing.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fait, and you may &s;ay that, my Lord&mdash;for I never minded any thing; and, I believe, I look full as much like a ro&s;e as your&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fore gad, my valiant Captain, thy ap|pearance is a little too terrific for the tranquillity of my country-&s;eat&mdash;thou mu&s;t really change that warlike habit of thine, and think of more peaceable &s;ervices.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>O be ea&s;y now, my Lord, and let my habits alone. To be &s;ure I've a cu&s;tom of looking pretty manly in the face, and that's no common habit now among&s;t gentlemen; and, thanks to St. Patrick, I have a tolerable good con&s;titution;&mdash;but &s;o much the better for your Lord&s;hip, for I have been making pretty free with it the&s;e ten years pa&s;t&mdash;for the &s;ake of your reputation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;ha! Swagger, it is not thy con&s;ti|tution I complain of, but thy head&mdash;thy crazy head, that cannot carry into execution the glorious enterprizes I plan for thee. What is the cabinet without the key? or any of the Boards without the fir&s;t Lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, boo woo, don't be after comparing me to a board, and prai&s;ing your own qualifications, when you know they're all mine: you have forgot what u&s;e I was to you when we travell'd together; how I con&s;tantly remember'd what was to happen, and carried away all the things we left behind us&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, I remember you pocketed the old bills, when I had paid the reck'ning.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Faith and troth but I paid the reck'ning too&mdash;for the &s;core was mark'd upon my back.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, but I forget all this while the
<PB N="8" REF="12">
intere&s;ts of my deare&s;t Loui&s;a&mdash;a rapturous lover like me <STAGE>(coughing)</STAGE> does not always carry his wits about him&mdash;What an&s;wer did'&s;t thou bring from her?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>O fait, and it was very difficult to remem|ber, for it was no an&s;wer at all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>How! what!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, to be &s;ure, the old knight here, Sir Gregory Glovetop, could not help thinking my <HI>t&ecirc;te-&agrave;-t&ecirc;te</HI> vi&s;its to Madam Loui&s;a, e&s;pecially as you were al|ways one of the party, would do his daughter Harriet no good&mdash;&s;o he has &s;ent madam a-packing, that's all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Loui&s;a turned out of Sir Gregory's hou&s;e! what havoc I make among&s;t the women!&mdash;But is &s;he really turn'd adrift on my account?&mdash;Harkee, &s;irrah, don't you know that I am all feeling&mdash;a ma&s;s of combu&s;tible &s;en&s;ibility? ha! ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, what if you are&mdash;there's no occa&s;ion to go off here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, art thou ignorant that I con&s;ider my&s;elf the &s;ole and undivided property of the ladies, and that I build <HI>my</HI> reputation upon theirs?&mdash;Have not I &s;et my heart upon carrying off this fair widow? and do I ever fail in matters of love? <STAGE>(coughing)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, and hav'n't you &s;acrific'd the poor ereature's happine&s;s, by frightening away her friends from her? and can't you be &s;atisfied with the di&s;tre&s;s you have already occa&s;ioned, and the ill reports that are &s;pread about her?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;there are no ill reports that I have been &s;ucce&s;sful&mdash;&s;o what di&s;tre&s;s is there to &s;atisfy me? Fly therefore about the neighbourhood, and find where my trea&s;ure is hidden.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>O now, if that is all your trea&s;ure, be quiet and ea&s;y; becau&s;e why, when one trea&s;ure is lo&s;t, another may be found&mdash;that's my philo&s;ophy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="9" REF="13">
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold thy profane jargon&mdash;do&s;t thou think the delicacy of my pa&s;&s;ions are &s;o ea&s;ily charm'd? and that I am form'd horribly robu&s;t, as thou art, with|out a grain of &s;en&s;ibility&mdash;a heart of &s;tone, and nerves of ca&s;t iron?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nerves of ca&s;t iron!&mdash;upon my word, and very pretty things too. It may be the fa&s;hion to be &s;ick to death, and <HI>&s;en&s;ible</HI> alive, as they call it, to every thing; but, thanks to St. Patrick, I never was either one or the other; and I hope I never &s;hall.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't put me in a pa&s;&s;ion, Captain&mdash;but let me not &s;ee thy face again till thou ha&s;t found her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(turns him&s;elf away)</STAGE> O, to be &s;ure, I will face about, if you plea&s;e; and, if I can't find her, when I return why I mu&s;t come in again in the &s;ame manner as I go out. It is only walking backwards, you know.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit, walking forwards.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(coughing)</STAGE> What a dreadful tax it is up$n a man of fa&s;hion, to have his peace interrupted by the impertinence of a woman's beauty!&mdash;That a pair of black eyes &s;hould totally relax the fibres, and a fine &s;hape de|&s;troy the whole nervous &s;y&s;tem!&mdash;Well, I have nothing for it but a good con&s;titution to depend upon.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit, coughing.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">An Apartment in <HI>LORD HECTIC</HI>'s hou&s;e.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LADY BETTY WORMWOOD, <HI>and Mi&s;s</HI> PENELOPE ZODIAC, <HI>di&s;puting.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you, Lady Betty, that &s;cience, and a knowledge of mathematics, geography, and tactics, is the fir&s;t &s;tone in the character of an unmarried wo|man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="10" REF="14">
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure, Mi&s;s Penelope Zodiac, geography and tactics are unque&s;tionably the principal &s;upports of a woman's character; though, owing to the unaccountable ignorance of mankind, three parts of our &s;ex get married without any &s;uch perfections.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Get married!&mdash;&s;o much the wor&s;e. If women's minds were properly filled with elaborate re|&s;earches, they would have no vacancy for &s;uch un&s;eemly ideas. Think of the divine charms of philo&s;ophy&mdash;pure ethics&mdash;to wander from pole to pole, and to &s;wim in the milky way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Undoubtedly, Madam, if a lady mu&s;t &s;wim, the milky way is as well as any other; and, to a roving mind, the wandering from pole to pole may be very delightful; but I &s;hould imagine the le&s;s a woman wanders the better.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, thank Heaven, my mind, I am proud to own, has never de&s;cended &s;o low as to con|template that improper creature a man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>For goodne&s;s' &s;ake let us then change the di&s;cour&s;e, and talk about a woman.&mdash;What think you of Loui&s;a, the object of my brother's pre&s;ent pur&s;uit?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>What that affected widow that lives at Sir Gregory Glovetop's, and pretends to be fond of nature; though &s;he knows no more of the planetary &s;y&s;tem, than I do of making a pudding?&mdash;Oh, I dete&s;t &s;uch audacious creatures, as every lady of &s;entiment ought to do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>For my part, I believe the wretch has the confidence to think that my brother entertains ho|nourable de&s;igns upon her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Entirely owing to her ignorance of mathematics: had &s;he been &s;tudying Euclid &s;he could not have had &s;uch a thought.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Perhaps not&mdash;but, le&s;t the lady &s;hould
<PB N="11" REF="15">
never take to &s;tudies of that kind, I will tell you what I have done: you mu&s;t know, though I am naturally of a tender di&s;po&s;ition, and extremely aver&s;e to every thing that's cruel&mdash;yet, for the &s;ake of example, I have pre|vailed upon old Sir Gregory to turn her out of his hou&s;e. My brother will mo&s;t probably forget her; and the minx will be happily left to &s;tarve in &s;ome di&s;tant country, &s;o that we &s;ha'n't be &s;hock'd with her di&s;tre&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>A very kind precaution&mdash;but indeed, Lady Betty Wormwood, your brother is a &s;ad libertine&mdash;quite an ignis fatuus, as the learned call it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>He certainly is, and therefore he had much better remain &s;ingle, and keep his fortune in his own family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure, the whole world had better remain &s;ingle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>He will be delightfully di&s;appointed when he finds the bird is flown. I have a very great regard for my brother, but I do love to &s;ee him mor|tified.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>So do I, Lady Betty&mdash;becau&s;e he will never allow that we women have &s;uperior under&s;tandings to the men. Oh, what was Plato, for in&s;tance, to the queen of Sheba? or what would the duke of Marlbo|rough have done with the maid of Orleans?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LORD HECTIC.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Done with her!&mdash;why whatever he pleas'd&mdash;men of prowe&s;s are always &s;ucce&s;sful&mdash;for in&s;tance, my&s;elf <STAGE>(coughing).</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg, my Lord, you will not &s;hock my hearing with any improper compliments to any body&mdash;you will plea&s;e to recollect I am an unmarried woman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, my brother is only going to di&s;play his own qualifications; and &s;urely they can't &s;hock any lady.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="12" REF="16">
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, to be &s;ure&mdash;for egad I adore the whole &s;ex&mdash;&s;trive to make them all happy, <STAGE>(coughing)</STAGE> from the duche&s;s down to the milk-maid; and, to do my|&s;elf ju&s;tice, few people more fortunate <STAGE>(coughing).</STAGE> Wo|men of &s;cience, as you call them, are the ea&s;ie&s;t things in the world; as, for in&s;tance&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(alarm'd)</STAGE> Ble&s;s me! I hope your lord|&s;hip is not going to be rude.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Rude, Mi&s;s Penelope!&mdash;in this company <STAGE>(&s;urveying her)</STAGE>&mdash;I have not &s;uch an idea.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, my Lord, I blu&s;h for your &s;ublunary conduct;&mdash;why can't you indulge your genius in a nobler way, and attach your&s;elf to the heavenly bo|dies, as I do&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why I do attach my&s;elf to the heavenly bodies; only I don't look among the &s;tars for them, as you d$.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my word, if your lord&s;hip keeps going on in this manner I mu&s;t quit the premi&s;es&mdash;I &s;hall be afraid to tru&s;t my&s;elf under your roof&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Mi&s;s Penelope Zodiac, don't have the lea&s;t apprehen&s;ion&mdash;you are perfectly &s;afe, believe me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't know that, my Lord&mdash;when you are carrying on your intrigues directly within our vortex, as one may &s;ay. I am told here is a wanton wi|dow hard by.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! the widow's &s;ituation at pre&s;ent is not quite &s;o agreeable. But we &s;eem to be playing at cro&s;s purpo&s;es; &s;o, ladies, I'll attend your tea-equipage immediately&mdash;I have two or three morning petitioners to di&s;patch, who are waiting without: they won't de|tain me long; for I always promi&s;e every thing they a&s;k, to &s;horten conver&s;ation&mdash;and then you &s;hall &s;ee what havoc good &s;pirits and &s;ound health <STAGE>(coughing)</STAGE> can make amid&s;t your French rolls and butter. <STAGE><HI>[Exit</HI> Lady Betty.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="13" REF="17">
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(going)</STAGE> Au revoir, my Lord.&mdash;But I wi&s;h you wou'd not turn &s;o much upon your own axis.</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Exit</HI> Mi&s;s Penelope.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very whim&s;ical advice.&mdash;Egad, I be|lieve the old &s;pin&s;ter wants me to take a turn with her.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE IV.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">An Apartment in an old Hou&s;e belonging to Sir <HI>GREGORY GLOVETOP,</HI> furni&s;hed in a very antique manner, decorated with Ornaments of Heraldry, Coats of Arms, Badges, Ban|ners, and antient Orders.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>SIR GREGORY,</HI> &s;omewhat heated, followed by <HI>HARRIET.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my decorum, Harriet, I am quite a&s;hamed of you.&mdash;<Q>&startq;&endq;You have no idea of punctillo, and form, and etiquette, and ceremony; not an atom of the old court about you, as my name is Sir Gregory Glovetop.</Q></P>
</SP>
<Q>&startq;&endq;

<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Con&s;ider, dear Sir, the difference of our years: &s;aving your pre&s;ence, it is not to be expected that I &s;hould wi&s;h to have any thing old about me.</P>
</SP></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>"Sir Gregory."</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, child, I &s;wear by my knight|hood, you are as rude and unpoli&s;hed as a beef-eater.&mdash;Will you never entertain a proper re&s;pect for antient cu&s;|toms?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord, papa, am I to be blamed, becau&s;e I have the misfortune not to be &s;o old as my grandmother?&mdash;Be&s;ides, I have been bred up in the country, and can|not have had an opportunity of &s;eeing or improving from courts.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! not had an opportunity of im|proving! han't you &s;een me? Study my manners and ad|dre&s;s;
<PB N="14" REF="18">
and then learn what would be becoming in a young woman. A fine example, indeed, thrown away, if I, who have lived in the circle, pre&s;ided at drawing|rooms, bow'd at levees, eat cake and caudle-royal, &s;hould have danc'd, and bow'd, and eat for no purpo&s;e!&mdash;I beg I may hear no more of this uncourtier-like friend|&s;hip you profe&s;s for Loui&s;a.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sure, &s;ir, our long intimacy, her amiable di&s;|po&s;ition, and her hard fortune, together with the manner in which &s;he was obliged to quit our hou&s;e, after having been admitted into it as a re&s;ident, mu&s;t leave a regret upon my mind, which I hope you will allow not quite unju&s;tifiable.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>Quite the rever&s;e, I a&s;&s;ure you; and not a precedent for it in the red book. I allow no friend&s;hip, but of form: when people are out of place, the ceremony is to forget them&mdash;a &s;queeze by the hand&mdash;or a proper nod of the head&mdash;but no more;&mdash;no &s;orrow upon the countenance, except at a court-mourning.&mdash;That was the rule in my time, and I never can forget the lord chamberlain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, my dear papa, was it not rather unkind to compel my unhappy friend to retire from beneath your roof, becau&s;e that odious Lord Hectic would plague her with un&s;ought-for &s;olicitations; and to force her and her little infant to &s;eek a new habitation, for impertinencies which hurt her peace more than they cou'd yours?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h, child! Lords have great privi|leges, and, at the old court, carried a dignity which, with a proper dre&s;s, a full-bottom'd periwig, and a &s;hort &s;word, were truly re&s;pectable.&mdash;But, let me tell you, that no per&s;on who has had the honour of dining with the corps diplomatique, can or will brook great coats and dirty boots&mdash;I mean no offenc$ to the peerage.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear papa, can you imagine, that a
<PB N="15" REF="19">
mind like Loui&s;a's, &s;o worn with anxiety, can thus ea&s;ily regain its happine&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, I always thought &s;he was too pen|&s;ive for a well-bred per&s;on. You &s;hould have &s;een me at a birth-night, bowing, and &s;impering, and &s;queezing, and nodding, and handing wine among peers and peere&s;&s;es, laced down to my &s;hoes; &s;tockings rolled up; and periwig in full float; then, I think, you would have taken me for &s;omebody&mdash;every feature curl'd into a &s;mile, and not one look of thought upon my countenance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>But &s;urely, grief was natural to the tender|ne&s;s of a di&s;po&s;ition like Loui&s;a's&mdash;her fortunes were of the humble&s;t kind, and &s;he had probably lo&s;t the hu&s;band of her fonde&s;t affection.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>The French Duche&s;s of Pantoufle lo&s;t five hu&s;bands, and always appear'd in her place.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, Sir, con&s;ider the unprotected &s;tate of her little one&mdash;the &s;weete&s;t boy! you could not help being plea&s;ed with him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, the boy might have done for a page&mdash;I had &s;ome thoughts of teaching him the true court-&s;tep my&s;elf&mdash;but that mini&s;try are out, and &s;o we'll think no more about them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear &s;ir, picture to your&s;elf her &s;ituation&mdash;alone, de&s;erted&mdash;no friend to &s;ooth&mdash;no parent to pro|tect.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, there again;&mdash;her father is &s;till liv|ing; why don't he &s;end an envoy, or plenipo, to the place of her re&s;idence?&mdash;you &s;ay, he was di&s;plea&s;ed with her marriage; what of that? there is no occa&s;ion for affection to pre&s;erve ceremony&mdash;I remember Count Bal|derblou&s;ki, from Poland, had no intercour&s;e with his child for twenty years; yet they always kept up deco|rums, &s;olemnized their birth-days at five hundred miles di&s;tance&mdash;and hated each other with civility.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="16" REF="20">
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Wou'd Loui&s;a had a father's home, as I have, to retreat to, in&s;tead of being forc'd to &s;eek an a&s;ylum among &s;trangers; who, unacquainted with the gentlene&s;s of her di&s;po&s;ition, may aggravate the &s;orrows which they cannot feel!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can I help it, child, if every one is not &s;o well ver&s;ed in politene&s;s as I am?&mdash;Be&s;ides, I am natu|rally gentle, and have &s;aid to her a thou&s;and times, that no one would be &s;o charitable to her as my&s;elf.&mdash;Ma'am, &s;ays I to her, in the kinde&s;t manner, you are left de&s;ti|tute&mdash;a kind of outca&s;t&mdash;but what of that? behave properly, and I will conde&s;cend to give you a certain degree of con&s;equence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, Sir, recal your cruel decree, and in|dulge your Harriet with the plea&s;ure of bringing back under the &s;ame roof the friend and companion of her earlie&s;t years.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, child! when I have told you I am gentle, dare you pre&s;cribe to me how I ought to act! I that was the corner-&s;tone of the old court; brought up among&s;t maids of honour and bed-chamber ladies, <Q>&startq;admitted to the back-&s;tairs, and have peep'd through the clo&s;et key-hole.&endq;</Q> O, I am petrified by your pre|&s;umption!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear papa, I hope you are not offended at my pre&s;uming to plead the cau&s;e of friend&s;hip&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, child, I am offended.&mdash;Now, indeed, people don't know when they ought to be &s;o;&mdash;affect to be plea&s;ed, when they are quite out of humour; laugh at every thing; and want a demeanor in their re&s;entments: but, thank Heaven, I am better acquainted with dignity.&mdash;The old Lord Burleigh, when he was offended&mdash;he&mdash;hum!&mdash;I believe he walked off, and &s;aid nothing.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit, retiring backwards &s;tately and &s;ulkily.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(&s;ola)</STAGE> And mu&s;t I &s;acrifice to the&s;e unmeaning forms of my father each emotion of my heart? for&s;ake my
<PB N="17" REF="21">
virtuous and much-injured friend, in who&s;e &s;weet &s;ociety I have enjoyed &s;o many happy hours, and from who&s;e gene|rous coun&s;els my inexperienced youth has reaped &s;o much advantage?&mdash;No; every &s;entiment of gratitude and hu|manity forbid it. I have already con&s;ulted my Belcour on the occa&s;ion: his tenderne&s;s for me is, I think, &s;incere; and he mu&s;t doubtle&s;s prize that warmth of friend&s;hip in his Harriet's bo&s;om, which may lead him to expect &s;he can as forcibly feel a &s;ofter pa&s;&s;ion. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<TRAILER>END OF TH$ FIRST ACT.</TRAILER>
