<DIV2>
<PB N="18" REF="26">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">A retir'd Cottage, with a View of the Country: A Seat at the Foot of a Tree, near the Door of the Cottage.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>LOUISA</HI> coming forward with a Book.</STAGE>
<P>HOW vain is the philo&s;ophy which books would preach up to us, to a&s;&s;uage the real angui&s;h of the heart!&mdash;The wounded mind, that wanders to them for con&s;olation, returns with double force to home-felt grief; and, while it feels poignantly for feign'd di&s;tre&s;s, with added pangs will contemplate its own.&mdash;Then how can I expect to find relief from &s;tudy? mark'd out for af|fliction from life's earlie&s;t dawn, its ripening day but brings encrea&s;e of woe.&mdash;Alas! that charming &s;ea&s;on of youth, when all around, gay, flattering expectation gilds the &s;cene, and every coming hour &s;eems wing'd with new delight, for me teem'd only with misfortune!&mdash;Born with a heart too tender, and perhaps too &s;anguine, I fond|ly plann'd delu&s;ive &s;chemes of happine&s;s, which Fate de|creed I never &s;hould enjoy. One friend,&mdash;one only friend the world had left me; &s;he too I now mu&s;t lo&s;e.&mdash;Poor Harriet!&mdash;<Q>&startq;tho' tormented by the caprices of a weak father, may'&s;t thou never &s;uffer half the mi&s;ery of thy di&s;tracted friend!&endq;</Q> My child too,&mdash;my little &s;miling boy,&mdash;he mu&s;t be for a time de&s;erted.&mdash;Alas! who knows how long?</P>
<STAGE><PB N="19" REF="27">
Enter <HI>ANNA</HI> and the child from the cottage.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Anna.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear lady, every thing is ready, as you order'd, and your writing-box and the miniature picture are left upon your table.&mdash;But, my lov'd mi&s;tre&s;s&mdash;forgive my boldne&s;s&mdash;can you really bear to leave your &s;weet companion behind you?&mdash;will you indeed tru&s;t him with me while you are gone?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tru&s;t him with you, my Anna! Alas&punc; to whom el&s;e can I bequeath him?&mdash;The unfeeling world hath barr'd each door again&s;t him, and poverty's hard hand leads forth his infant &s;teps.&mdash;Now, too, he mu&s;t forego a parent's tenderne&s;s;&mdash;but I hope our &s;eparation will not be long; and you, who feel for him a mother's love, will, I think, guard him with a mother's anxiety.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Child.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, mayn't I go too?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, my angel,&mdash;my journey would fatigue you&mdash;its object is but to do you &s;ervice&mdash;may its wi&s;hes be accompli&s;hed! and may my darling child's maturing years be happier than his morn of life has promi&s;ed!&mdash;Here, Anna, take this trifle <STAGE>(giving a pur&s;e)</STAGE> I wi&s;h it were larger for your &s;ake&mdash;but Fortune allows me to be profu&s;e of nothing but my thankfulne&s;s;&mdash;it will &s;erve, perhaps, to defray the nece&s;&s;ary expences of my Fred'ric; for the re&s;t, di&s;po&s;e of it as you like.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Anna.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray now, my dear lady, excu&s;e me.&mdash;Indeed I cannot accept of it.&mdash;You have been always a tender mi&s;tre&s;s, and I have &s;av'd a &s;omething in your &s;ervice,&mdash;a trifle indeed, but how can I employ it better than in returning it to the dear child of her from who&s;e goodne&s;s fir&s;t it came?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold, hold; your genero&s;ity oppre&s;&s;es, over|powers me&mdash;but &s;ome one is coming this way:&mdash;retire, therefore, for a moment&mdash;I would not that &s;trangers
<PB N="20" REF="28">
&s;hould know how &s;en&s;ibly I'm affected, by the exalted behaviour of my more than friend.</P>
<STAGE>[They go into the cottage.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>HARRIET</HI> ha&s;tily.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>My deare&s;t Loui&s;a, I would not lo&s;e an in&s;tant in ha&s;tening to you, the moment I cou'd e&s;cape from my father. But wherefore the&s;e tears?&mdash;Your boy&mdash;my little play-fellow, I hope, is well.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, very well;&mdash;I grieve only to be the cau&s;e of &s;o much trouble to my Harriet.&mdash;Alas! I &s;eem born to give unea&s;ine&s;s to all my friends;&mdash;at lea&s;t the few I have left.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, my Loui&s;a, conquer this de&s;pon|dency&mdash;indeed you have a great many friends&mdash;every good mind mu&s;t be &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>How &s;oothing is your &s;en&s;ibility!&mdash;why am I flatter'd with kindne&s;s, only to make the parting with it more &s;evere?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Parting, Loui&s;a! what is it you mean? Do not imagine this mi&s;under&s;tanding can long continue&mdash;a&s;&s;ure your&s;elf we &s;hall &s;oon again be happy; and this little interval will but increa&s;e the charms of our renewed &s;ociety.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Impo&s;&s;ible&mdash;my re&s;olution is taken:&mdash;there is a per&s;on who&s;e regard, notwith&s;tanding long neglect, I &s;till hold it my duty to &s;olicit:&mdash;once he has refu&s;ed, cruelly refu&s;ed to hear me&mdash;&s;hou'd his unkindne&s;s &s;till continue&mdash;but no matter.&mdash;At a di&s;tance, Harriet, I may perhaps have courage to reveal to you a &s;tory, which my blu&s;hes wou'd prevent me from doing in your pre&s;ence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(Changing her manner)</STAGE> What then, my fair friend,&mdash;there is a &s;ome one who&s;e regard you are more anxious to &s;olicit than that of your humble &s;ervant.
<PB N="21" REF="29">
&mdash;In truth I ought to have con&s;ider'd that immoderate grief in a widow, a young, hand&s;ome widow, like you, was not altogether &s;o natural.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, Harriet, you mi&s;take me much.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>In truth but I do not.&mdash;No wonder that the gallant addre&s;&s;es of our neighbour, Colonel Quorum, that military di&s;pen&s;er of warrants, and &s;ettler of di&s;putes, &s;hould all be lo&s;t upon you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lo&s;t upon me indeed!&mdash;O my gay, &s;prightly, yet feeling friend! wou'd I cou'd always be the occa&s;ion of calling forth that charming vivacity! The Colonel, I agree with you, has certainly an excellent heart, and not|with&s;tanding his violence, and his continued &s;wearing&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Swearing!&mdash;Oh, he is a ju&s;tice of peace, you know, and is us'd to it;&mdash;be&s;ides, a lover &s;hou'd always have a good &s;tock of oaths to begin with;&mdash;but, laughing apart, Loui&s;a, he has an ample fortune, and is &s;in|cerely attached to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>How can you talk to me &s;eriou&s;ly on &s;uch a &s;ubject?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, if your affections are really engaged, I mention it no more;&mdash;but otherwi&s;e I &s;hou'd have &s;aid, that your duty to the decea&s;ed has been more than paid; and, though I cannot imagine that here your heart wou'd be deeply intere&s;ted, yet you have a child, who&s;e wel|fare is your care&mdash;independence is offer'd to him: he has no father's fortune, give him therefore a claim to inherit one.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray drop the &s;ubject,&mdash;perhaps he has a fa|ther, and may not a&s;k the bounties of a &s;tranger;&mdash;per|haps&mdash;what am I &s;aying?&mdash;Pray Harriet, believe me, I was thinking of &s;omething el&s;e, and did not properly at|tend to your di&s;cour&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(taking her hand)</STAGE> And is there, my Loui&s;a, any thing which you dare not reveal to your friend?
<PB N="22" REF="30">
Some private grief that you think her unworthy to be tru&s;ted with.&mdash;Tho' all your Harriet's inmo&s;t thoughts have long been lodg'd in her Loui&s;a's bo&s;om.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>PICKAXE</HI> ha&s;tily.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, I am &s;o glad I have found you: for I've been in every corner of the pari&s;h the&s;e two days, with a me&s;&s;age from my ma&s;ter, Colonel Quorum, and no tidings cou'd be heard of you.&mdash;So I went into the ale-hou&s;e hard by; for there, thinks I&mdash;but I beg pardon for being out of breath.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>There is no occa&s;ion to beg pardon,&mdash;but pray don't be in &s;uch a hurry;&mdash;you'll &s;uffocate your|&s;elf, Mr. Pickaxe.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>True, madam, I cannot talk &s;o fa&s;t as the women, as I &s;ay to my wife;&mdash;but no matter for that:&mdash;&s;o, going into the ale-hou&s;e, I heard as how a &s;trange lady, which I knew mu&s;t be you, was come to live here|abouts, and that Sir Gregory Glovetop,&mdash;I beg your papa's pardon, Mi&s;s Harriet&mdash;had turn'd Madam out of doors, which was being a little upon the rumbu&s;ticle with a lady, &s;ays I,&mdash;but no matter for that;&mdash;I never talk of any body's affairs but my own.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you keep to that re&s;olution we &s;hall never hear any thing of your ma&s;ter's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>O Madam, never fear him&mdash;he'll make him|&s;elf heard when he's in a pa&s;&s;ion;&mdash;and, indeed, to &s;peak by the &s;tatutes, as ma&s;ter calls it, he is in a very great pa&s;&s;ion for Madam Loui&s;a; for the moment he heard how your lady&s;hip was treated, quite no better than a vagrant, he &s;wore he would commit the whole pari&s;h, and Sir Gregory Glovetop into the bargain&mdash;but Lord, Sir, &s;ays I&mdash;its all the better for your wor&s;hip, for the lady, as I may &s;ay, being a little at a nonplus, and not knowing
<PB N="23" REF="31">
where to turn her&s;elf, who knows but &s;he may face about to your wor&s;hip's regimentals?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Mr. Pickaxe, you &s;eem to have form'd a very ju&s;t opinion of the &s;ex&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord, Ma'am! as I &s;aid to my ma&s;ter when he had done &s;wearing, I know them&mdash;Madam Loui&s;a mu&s;t be in trouble: &s;he is not like Mi&s;s Harriet, as I &s;aid, gallanting it away of her own accord with the gentleman in the green walk, becau&s;e &s;he is in love with him her|&s;elf&mdash;No, no, Madam Loui&s;a wants pre&s;&s;ing, and a bit of vexation&mdash;and then &s;he'll come to&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sure, my hone&s;t friend, you cannot think I want vexation; however, I am not going to be angry, for if &s;uch is your interpretation, Mr. Pickaxe, it will be very dangerous to be vex'd in your company.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why it's my fault, as I &s;ay to my&s;elf, to be &s;incere;&mdash;for, as I &s;aid to his wor&s;hip, what can you want with a wife? have not you the di&s;turbances of the whole pari&s;h to &s;ettle, and to &s;wear (I mean to hear people &s;wear) from morning till night&mdash;and then, &s;ince you took to train|ing volunteers, &s;ays I, and to firing great guns, and have peace neither at home nor abroad, what the Devil, &s;ays I to his wor&s;hip, can you want with a wife?</P>
</SP>
<Q>&startq;&endq;<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>And what could his wor&s;hip an&s;wer to that?</P>
</SP></Q>
<Q>&startq;<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, madam, its my fault not to be minded, becau&s;e I &s;ay little; but I verily believe as how, if Ma|dam Loui&s;a wou'd but li&s;ten to his addre&s;&s;es, there is not a ju&s;tice of peace in the whole hundred that wou'd commit matrimony &s;ooner&mdash;</P>
</SP>&endq;</Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my word, Mr. Pickaxe, the Colonel has no occa&s;ion to &s;ay much for him&s;elf, while he has &s;o able an advocate.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, madam, a few kind words from you wou'd make a man of him again; for, to &s;ay truth, he is
<PB N="24" REF="32">
&s;adly out of &s;orts&mdash;can't &s;ign a warrant in peace.&mdash;Do, Madam, &s;ent him a little comfort, be it ever &s;o cold;&mdash;do but &s;ay you love him now&mdash;if its only to plea&s;e him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, my good friend, I cannot &s;ay that to any man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Ma'am, if you can't love him, &s;ay you'll marry him, and let t'other come by and by;&mdash;I'm &s;ure Mi&s;s Harriet here wou'd not be &s;o difficult.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg, Mr. Pickaxe, you will not be fancying things about me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fancying things!&mdash;No, Ma'am, I leave that to the gentleman in the green walk.&mdash;I a&s;k pardon for being &s;incere;&mdash;but, as I was &s;aying, if you wou'd only be &s;o good as to give him a kind look or two, ju&s;t as much as to `&s;ay I &s;ee you,' he'd go quite out of his wits, and be the happie&s;t man in the world.&mdash;Come, Ma'am, I'll tell him you like his carriage&mdash;his air, and the calf of his leg.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I reque&s;t you will tell him no &s;uch thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>That you think him a fine officer, and a good ju&s;tice of peace.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I make no doubt but he is both; but let me intreat you not to mention that I &s;ay any thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Ma'am; then I'll only &s;ay that I &s;aid it&mdash;and that you &s;aid nothing. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! upon my word there is &s;omething entertaining in the ab&s;urdities of that fellow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, for they have occa&s;ioned a momentary &s;u&s;pen&s;ion of my &s;orrows.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>For Heaven's &s;ake, my dear Loui&s;a, explain to me the my&s;tery which, before we were interrupted, your la&s;t words conveyed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Harriet! &s;pare me on that &s;ubject.&mdash;It is a long and melancholy tale, that will require a re&s;olution which at pre&s;ent I cannot command.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will you then for&s;ake me? and leave her,
<PB N="25" REF="33">
whom you u&s;ed to call the partner of your heart, a &s;tranger to tho&s;e di&s;quiets which &s;he would gladly participate, and anxiou&s;ly endeavour to &s;ooth?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>My kind, my tender Harriet, a&s;&s;ure your&s;elf, co&s;t me what it will, before we finally &s;eparate, you &s;hall be fully acquainted with the &s;ad &s;tory of Loui&s;a's woes&mdash;then perhaps my &s;often'd friend will find another and a newer tear to give to my misfortunes&mdash;perhaps &s;he'll cla&s;p me nearer to her heart&mdash;perhaps &s;he'll hold me at a fearful di&s;tance. However it may turn out&mdash;believe me, the parting pang will deeply rend my bo&s;om; and ab&s;ence, time, nor circum&s;tance, &s;hall ever era&s;e the fond remem|brance of my Harriet's virtues.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit <HI>Loui&s;a</HI> into her cottage&mdash;<HI>Harriet</HI> oppo&s;ite.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">An Apartment in <HI>LORD&punc; HECTIC'S</HI> Hou&s;e.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LORD HECTIC, LOVELESS, <HI>and</HI> BELCOUR.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, Belcour, I know you and your friend Lovele&s;s mu&s;t laugh at us country '&s;quires. You London gentlemen have no ta&s;te for rural charms, and the ruddy looks of the country&mdash;hem! hem!&mdash;for my part, however, give me the old Engli&s;h con&s;titution.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope your Lord&s;hip feels no nece&s;&s;ity for that wi&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Me! hem! by no means&mdash;I &s;peak only of the charms of ri&s;ing early in a morning, taking a long ride, breathing the keen air, hem!&mdash;and pur&s;uing tho&s;e active plea&s;ures that &s;trengthen and invigorate, and make us Engli&s;hmen the terrors of the world.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bravo, my Lord!&mdash;to &s;ay truth I &s;hou'd not have &s;u&s;pected your having a ta&s;te for rural &s;ports, &s;hoot|ing, fox-hunting, and the et caeteras of a country life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="26" REF="34">
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>No more I have&mdash;do you think I want to rival my game-keeper?&mdash;Tho&s;e were the barbarou$ arts of our ance&s;tors in the days of boxing, who affected to be &s;tronger, hem! than a gentleman ought to be&mdash;No, no, I mean the little innocent delights&mdash;the &s;miling wreath, hem!&mdash;and myrtle bower.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, my Lord, and the &s;miling beauties in that bower&mdash;a London out of town&mdash;the charms of Pall|mall in the groves of Hamp&s;hire&mdash;that, I pre&s;ume, is your Lord&s;hip's rural life; at lea&s;t if we may tru&s;t the gallant chronicles of your Lord&s;hip's &s;eat.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>O fie! Belcour&mdash;But do they &s;ay that I'm no Jo&s;eph?&mdash;Juvenile follies, though, &s;hou'd be for|given&mdash;Some people do the&s;e things out of vanity, that &s;urprizes me; merely to be talk'd of, Mr. Lovele&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>And a mi&s;erable vanity it is, as your Lord|&s;hip ob&s;erves. Pa&s;&s;ion, indeed, may plead &s;ome excu&s;e for a momentary indulgence of it; but we &s;hould a&s;k no triumphs for our infirmities.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>True, Mr. Lovele&s;s&mdash;upon my word&mdash;a very&mdash;hem! hem! a very ju&s;t ob&s;ervation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye; but then, my Lord, that wou'd be too &s;evere a judgment, were it to extend to every little gallan|try with a grizette.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>True again, my dear Belcour; &s;ome al|lowance ought to be made, for, hem! the errors of the con&s;titution.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>And upon my word his Lord&s;hip has &s;ome right to plead weakne&s;s in that article&mdash;therefore I retract my opinion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, I fear you do but flatter me, now&mdash;for you know, Belcour, I am a little of a&mdash;hem! of a li|bertine; and, to tell you the truth&mdash;but your friend Love|le&s;s there looks &s;o moral and &s;erious, it's impo&s;&s;ible to &s;ay any thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="27" REF="35" MS="Y">
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, a town man&mdash;a perfect town man&mdash;don't mind him&mdash;a mere hypocrite.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Egad then I need not mind him&mdash;All a &s;ham, ha? not &s;o innocent as one wou'd imagine&mdash;never deceived any woman. <STAGE>(&s;miling.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;ha! no more than you have.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>I believe, my Lord, we have neither of us had any tran&s;action of that kind to boa&s;t of.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Boa&s;t of!&mdash;by no means&mdash;but, <HI>entre nous,</HI> I mu&s;t confe&s;s, without vanity, that I do &s;ucceed pretty well among&s;t the ladies&mdash;hem! A peer, you know, carries an appearance&mdash;a blaze, a hem! hem!&mdash;the girls are a&s;toni&s;hed&mdash;dre&s;s makes its way&mdash;and&mdash;a &s;tar for a gar|ter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>A garter! O that's the game you pur&s;ue.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure&mdash;woman is the game of a man of &s;pirit&mdash;hem! and I have found out &s;uch an ob|ject to cha&s;e; and, with your a&s;&s;i&s;tance, have no doubt but we &s;hall run it down.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can my a&s;&s;i&s;tance be nece&s;&s;ary? I fear, my Lord, it will not much avail.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, boys, you mu&s;t all a&s;&s;i&s;t; and fine &s;port we &s;hall have of it&mdash;for the lady affects to have virtue, and &s;tuff of that kind!&mdash;hem!&mdash;but in the country we do as you do in town, treat it as a pretence&mdash;mere pre|tence. Be&s;ides, I only begin with coaxing, and if that won't do, I proceed to vigorous mea&s;ures&mdash;hem! hem!&mdash;that's the way to &s;ucceed with the women&mdash;en't it, Bel|cour?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your Lord&s;hip, indeed, wants little in&s;truc|tion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no; 'egad I am pretty well at tho&s;e things&mdash;'tis not a little that &s;tops me. You wou'd go thro' any thing, I dare &s;ay, for a fine woman, Mr. Love|le&s;s. I mean it as a compliment&mdash;&s;o don't be a&s;hamed&mdash;
<PB N="28" REF="36">
But I won't be cruel to the poor creature. I intend to behave well; and, when my pa&s;&s;ion is over&mdash;hem! and if &s;he has &s;hewn a regard for me, I &s;hall marry her to a good &s;ort of fellow you may have &s;een in the hou&s;e&mdash;a Captain Swagger.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> CAPTAIN SWAGGER.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Faith, my Lord, and here I am, like the old proverb about bad news; and a &s;ad &s;tory I've found out, for Madam Loui&s;a's not to be heard of&mdash;&s;o I cou'd di&s;|cover nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>What then, you have found out a &s;ad &s;tory about nothing?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure&mdash;for they &s;ay &s;he is going to be married to Colonel Quorum.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Married! undone&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, &s;he has undone her&s;elf&mdash;in order that &s;he mayn't be ruined.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>What rea&s;on ha&s;t thou to think &s;o?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fir&s;t and foremo&s;t, as I was taking a little dram at the public-hou&s;e, ju&s;t to cool me&mdash;who &s;hou'd come by but Mr. Pickaxe, the Colonel's clerk&punc; or rather his aid-de-camp, in &s;uch a hurry&mdash;and, though I a&s;ked him to take a &s;up, he wou'd not open his lips upon the &s;ubject&mdash;upon my &s;houl he never refu&s;ed it before&mdash;a bad &s;ign that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure; an unu&s;ual &s;obriety looks like marriage&mdash;an unlucky omen for your Lord&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Secondly, when I pa&s;s'd the Colonel's hou&s;e, I ob&s;erved the great gun, that u&s;ed to be in the dog-ken|nel, was haul'd out before his door, by way of defence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing can be more probable&mdash;he expects an attack, I &s;uppo&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thirdly, upon the gra&s;s-plot before the
<PB N="29" REF="37" MS="Y">
parlour-window, what &s;hou'd I &s;ee, but his old regimental wai&s;tcoat and breeches laying out to air.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds, there's certainly a &s;omething in the wind.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>And, fourthly, the &s;tag's horns are taken down before the gate.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not a trait of the batchelor remaining&mdash;Why, your Lord&s;hip will lo&s;e the honour of providing for the lady&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gad zooks! after all the trouble&mdash;hem! hem! I have had, and the &s;ecrecy I have kept&mdash;to be di&s;appointed&mdash;hem!&mdash;no re&s;pect to a man of fa&s;hion! hem! Zounds! I will know where &s;he is gone to&mdash;that old fool, Sir Gregory Glovetop, &s;hall inform me why he dar'd turn a lady out of his hou&s;e that I &s;et my heart upon: hem! hem!&mdash;pray, gentlemen, excu&s;e the warmth of my con&s;titution.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, come, my Lord&mdash;be more tranquil&mdash;the old Engli&s;h con&s;titution was not di&s;turb'd in this manner; be&s;ides, I dare &s;ay, things are but half &s;o bad as they are related; for I make no doubt but the Captain &s;aw double the whole time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, Mr. Lovele&s;s&mdash;Sir, you who are a man of gallantry; think of the hard&s;hip of a beautiful young woman, taught&mdash;hem! hem!&mdash;taught prudence by an old fellow ju&s;t at the very la&s;t moment&mdash;hem! hem!</P>
<STAGE>(coughs violently.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Arrah now, my dear Lord, it will be <HI>your la&s;t</HI> moment, if you put your&s;elf into the&s;e pa&s;&s;ions about the women&mdash;for my part, I always advi&s;e following the ladies without any pa&s;&s;ion at all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>The coole&s;t advice, Captain, I ever heard in my life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gentlemen, excu&s;e me&mdash;you &s;ee I'm overcome by the difficulty of&mdash;hem! hem!&mdash;a con&s;titu|tional
<PB N="30" REF="38">
warmth&mdash;but your leave for a while&mdash;pray make free with every thing in my hou&s;e&mdash;hem!&mdash;my &s;i&s;ter and Mi&s;s Penelope will be glad to be treated without cere|mony!&mdash;hem!&mdash;but, hem!&mdash;Zounds!&mdash;I'll revenge this prudery by ruining the whole &s;ex.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit coughing and muttering.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(calling after him)</STAGE> Upon my &s;houl the &s;ex won't have much to fear&mdash;they can ruin your Lord&s;hip much ea&s;ier. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Lovele&s;s&mdash;do you not think your er|rors more venial, when you &s;ee &s;uch characters as Lord Hectic's&mdash;libertines again&s;t nature, and vicious without even the excu&s;es of inclination?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, my friend, I am too incorrigible in my repentance to receive any con&s;olation from the follies of others&mdash;nay more, do you know that I am Quixote enough in virtue to wi&s;h that Lord Hectic may be di&s;|appointed in his &s;chemes, and even to feel intere&s;ted that he &s;hould?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>I too am a convert to your &s;entiments,&mdash;my friend's continued dejection, while it grieves my heart&punc; corrects it.&mdash;I look upon the atchievements of gallantry with le&s;s ardor than heretofore; and I can conceive it full as inglorious to rob youth and innocence of its peace, as to pilfer the property of my neighbour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can you then wonder at my &s;en&s;ibility for this ill-fated fair one?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor Loui&s;a!&mdash;did you but know her&punc; you would indeed be intere&s;ted in her favour.&mdash;A beautiful young widow&punc; left with an infant child, in circum&s;tances the mo&s;t humiliating.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>What then, &s;he is really a woman of cha|racter, who&s;e afflictions are her only crimes?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my word, Lovele&s;s, I believe &s;o&mdash;I have often &s;een and convers'd with her at Sir Gregory's;
<PB N="31" REF="39">
and I confe&s;s, in &s;pite of my natural levity, I always re&s;pected the &s;adne&s;s that &s;eem'd to weigh her down.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, Belcour, if &s;uch is her &s;ituation, it would be criminal even to &s;uffer any aggravation of her misfortunes;&mdash;to be a pa&s;&s;ive &s;pectator of the di&s;tre&s;s we can alleviate, is unpardonable in any man&mdash;but it is cowardice in the extreme to remain unmov'd, when the virtuous &s;orrows of an afflicted woman demand our a&s;&s;i&s;tance. <STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">An old ca&s;tle, battlements, ba&s;tions, &amp;c. in whim&s;ical man|ner; an old moat, and a draw-bridge; a great gun at the entrance.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>COLONEL QUORUM</HI> from the ca&s;tle, with a book under his arm; <HI>PICKAXE</HI> following.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>And have you the confidence to &s;ay, that the lady &s;aid nothing?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>And plea&s;e your wor&s;hip, what could &s;he &s;ay better? for I mention'd every thing that was to be &s;aid in your honour's favour.&mdash;Ma'am, &s;ays I&mdash;you don't know what you he&s;itate about&mdash;a great ju&s;tice, and a good officer&mdash;under&s;tands the rules of the army&mdash;and has written a book about law&mdash;not very young indeed&mdash;but then has a fla&s;hy appearance&mdash;never in a pa&s;&s;ion in his whole life.&mdash;Such a temper, there's no de&s;cribing it.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, Pickaxe, you were right to &s;ay, I was of a mild di&s;po&s;ition&mdash;it goes a great way with the ladies&mdash;and as for the men&mdash;death and fury! I &s;hould like to &s;ee him who dur&s;t deny it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am &s;ure I am not the man to do it&mdash;&s;ub|mi&s;&s;ion
<PB N="32" REF="40">
provokes nobody, as I &s;ay&mdash;&s;o your honour can't be angry with me&mdash;but, if I might be &s;o bold to advi&s;e&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stop! I never take advice but on the parade, or at the quarter-&s;e&s;&s;ions&mdash;there, indeed&mdash;on the bench a ju&s;tice may &s;ubmit to coun&s;el&mdash;but, zounds! I flatter my&s;elf I can attack and &s;ubdue the ladies without any advice at all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>And the &s;ooner you do both the better; for I heard it whi&s;per'd, as how Madam Loui&s;a was about to leave the country&mdash;ah, your honour, tho' &s;he affects to take on, and to hold her&s;elf up&mdash;all is not as it &s;hould be.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold her&s;elf up!&mdash;I like her the better for it&mdash;I'll tell you what, Pickaxe, as the attendant of wealth and pro&s;perity, there is nothing &s;o in&s;ulting as pride; but, in more humble fortune, it &s;upports the cha|racter: and, damn me, may I never &s;wear an oath, if I &s;hall not be more flatter'd with her affection, &s;hou'd I find her pride the only &s;upport &s;he has;&mdash;&s;o I'm deter|min'd to marry her immediately. <STAGE>(Going.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stop, &s;top, your honour, indeed you had better a&s;k her con&s;ent fi$&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't provoke me&mdash;I tell you &s;he mu&s;t, &s;he &s;hall, con&s;ent&punc; be&s;ides, has not &s;he given me a thou&s;and proofs of her regard? Didn't &s;he look over my prayer-book la&s;t Sunday at church; and &s;mile, be|cau&s;e I chanc'd to open it at matrimony?&mdash;I'm con|vinc'd &s;he has a great &s;tock of tenderne&s;s for me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, your wor&s;hip&mdash;I hope it's not a laugh|ing &s;tock&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>For &s;hame, Pickaxe&mdash;did not &s;he &s;hed a tear the other day, when I hinted that love often made the be&s;t of us unhappy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes; the women can laugh and cry ju&s;t when they plea&s;e, a$ I &s;ay to my wife.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="33" REF="41">
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pickaxe, don't put me in a pa&s;&s;ion&mdash;Zounds and fire! &s;he &s;hall have me&mdash;why, I tell you, I have order'd the lawyer to attend me with the writings&mdash;and there's no &s;topping the law; that will have its cour&s;e&mdash;what the devil am I to do?&mdash;I &s;ay &s;he mu&s;t&mdash;I &s;ay he will&mdash;oh, here he comes.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>JANUS,</HI> with a parcel.</STAGE>
<P>Ma&s;ter Janus you are as punctual&mdash;</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; as punctual as a &s;ubpoena&mdash;here are the writings finely copied out. Very hand&s;ome provi&s;ion indeed on your part&mdash;but &s;aid lady, whoever &s;he is&mdash;left a blank for her name&mdash;&s;aid lady &s;eems not to have much property.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! that's neither here nor there.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Colonel, if &s;aid lady is willing, as the law &s;uppo&s;es &s;he is, we have nothing to do but to put her in in&s;tead of the blank: favour me, if you plea&s;e, with her de&s;cription, &s;pin&s;ter or widow, and re&s;iding in what pari&s;h&mdash;come, we can &s;ettle the bu&s;ine&s;s imme|diately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds! Ma&s;ter Janus, you are the only lawyer I ever knew in my life in a hurry to &s;ettle any bu&s;ine&s;s, except his bill: what &s;ignifies where and what the lady is?&mdash;probably &s;he has no pari&s;h&mdash;perhaps &s;he has&mdash;perhaps I may chu&s;e to marry&mdash;and perhaps I don't chu&s;e to marry at all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very true.&mdash;I remember a ca&s;e, George the 1&s;t. Strange's Reports, folio 22, page 231&mdash;if <HI>A.</HI> will marry <HI>B.</HI>&mdash;and <HI>B</HI> refu&s;es.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>What the devil have I to do with <HI>A.</HI> being refu&s;ed?&mdash;nobody has refu&s;ed me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe&punc;</SPEAKER>
<P>No, to be &s;ure&mdash;why the&s;e are <HI>&s;trange</HI> re|ports indeed, Ma&s;ter Janus.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="34" REF="42">
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ju&s;t the ca&s;e I was putting; for Coke very ju&s;tly ob&s;erves, that nobody can be married without their con&s;ent&mdash;for, &s;ays he, though the lady may be com|manded after, &s;he can't be commanded before;&mdash;and, ac|cording to Magna Charta&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>According to the devil!&mdash;What, am I not one of the Bench, and don't I under&s;tand Magna Charta, and Burn's Ju&s;tice, and all that, as well as you? Blood and confu&s;ion! am I to be in&s;tructed in the law of the land, and in the practice about women, at my time of life, by a pettifogging attorney?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Colonel, I hope no offence&mdash;but you de&s;ired me to draw up your marriage &s;ettlement, and here it is: how &s;hould I imagine you wanted to conceal the lady's name? Be&s;ides, the law knows no concealment, except in its practice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why you poor, paltry, up&s;tart, ill|looking bit of black letter, how dare you approach a man of con&s;equence, like me, with &s;uch language? Do you recollect who I am?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, if you mean to in&s;ult me, I do recollect who you are. I know you are half a ju&s;tice, half a &s;ol|dier&mdash;that you &s;trut about with a cockade in your hat, and a law-book under your arm.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go on, Sir&mdash;You are but an attorney, and therefore would di&s;grace the vengeance of my arm.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, an old gentleman too, that fancies him|&s;elf in love, and thinks he is going to be married&mdash;&s;ends for an hone&s;t attorney to draw up the &s;ettlement&mdash;and then don't know who he is to be married to.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds and damnation!&mdash;but I won't &s;wear&mdash;as I am cool, perfectly cool; but if I was not&mdash;fire and de&s;truction! I'd break every bone about you, and convert your &s;kin into &s;ome of your own parch|ment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="35" REF="43">
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h you wou'd&mdash;I &s;hou'd like nothing bet|ter, as the law ob&s;erves, than to &s;ee a very fine action written upon my back.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why you little rag of a remnant of the law you&mdash;I would have &s;aid ra&s;cal, but I know what you want, and &s;hall only call you an attorney.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's enough: mind, you call'd me a ra&s;cal&mdash;at lea&s;t you thought as much&mdash;and I'll do for you at the next a&s;&s;izes&mdash;Ni&s;i prius is the word&mdash;Call an attorney a ra&s;cal, indeed! <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(in a violent pa&s;&s;ion)</STAGE> Here's impudence with a vengeance! the limbs of law rebelling again&s;t the body of ju&s;tice&mdash;and yet there's no demanding &s;atisfac|tion.&mdash;By all the&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, your wor&s;hip, forget your indignation&mdash;con&s;id$r you're a &s;oldier.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Colonel Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do; and therefore, blood and fury! I will be reveng'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, but your honour, being a magi&s;trate, you know, mu&s;t act according to law.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(&s;oftening)</STAGE> True, Pickaxe, &s;o I mu&s;t&mdash;therefore I'll con&s;ult the Attorney General.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>It's a &s;hame that a gentleman bearing his Maje&s;ty's commi&s;&s;ion &s;hould be &s;o treated.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(heated)</STAGE> Zounds! bring me my nine|inch pi&s;tols.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pickaxe.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord, your wor&s;hip! I meant his Maje&s;ty's commi&s;&s;ion of the peace.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well con&s;idered, Pickaxe&mdash;&s;o take down the Statutes at Large, and follow me with them imme|diately. <STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<TRAILER>END OF THE SECOND ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<PB N="36" REF="44">
<HEAD>ACT III.</HEAD>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">A Meadow.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>BELCOUR</HI> and <HI>LOVELESS,</HI> meeting.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BELCOUR.</SPEAKER>
<P>WELL, Lovele&s;s, convinc'd by your arguments, I have at length &s;ummon'd re&s;olution enough to write a farewell letter to Harriot.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Believe me, Belcour, you will applaud your|&s;elf for every re&s;olution which tends to &s;ecure your honour and your peace.&mdash;An unworthy conque&s;t wou'd have given you a thou&s;and times more real &s;orrow, than even the &s;urrender of your deare&s;t wi&s;hes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very likely;&mdash;but, upon my $oul, I find it much le&s;s difficult to give advice than to take it.&mdash;I per|&s;uaded you to forget your Julia with great courage; but I cannot for&s;ake this little gip&s;ey of my own, without a thou&s;and pangs that I blu&s;h to &s;hew you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>In that ca&s;e, my dear friend, why forget her at all?&mdash;My advice was to forego a guilty, not an hone&s;t pur&s;uit.&mdash;Sacrifice to a worthy and ingenuous pa&s;&s;ion the fal&s;e &s;ugge&s;tions of pride; and meet the contemptible &s;coffs of the ignorant and unfeeling with the real feli|city of having &s;atisfied your own heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o I would&mdash;but con&s;ider my &s;ituation&mdash;I &s;hall incur the certain di&s;plea&s;ure of my uncle, and the relinqui&s;hing of all his po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ions.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>And what have I gain'd by the attainment of mine? What joys have wealth and &s;plendour brought to me?&mdash;an unhappy union with a woman, who&s;e only merits they were&mdash;and a ba&s;e de&s;ertion of another, who&s;e
<PB N="37" REF="45">
ingenuous mode&s;ty and native charms ever would have fix'd my heart&mdash;<Q>&startq;who&s;e tenderne&s;s and faithful love, wou'd have endear'd to me life's active day, and &s;weetly &s;olaced its declining years.&endq;</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>O! &s;pare me, Lovele&s;s&mdash;&s;pare us both;&mdash;a thou&s;and $$mes have I reproach'd my&s;elf with writing the letter I &s;ent this morning&mdash;but I tru&s;t to her genero&s;ity even again&s;t my&s;elf&mdash;&s;he will not wi&s;h me, I think, to &s;a|crifice&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you look upon it as a &s;acrifice, Belcour, I have done; I wou'd not wi&s;h her to pa&s;s her days with a man who might po&s;&s;ibly &s;uffer them to be embittered by regret. So let us turn our thoughts to her poor friend Loui&s;a; there, perhaps, our endeavours may be of &s;ome &s;ervice. For love, that &s;eems to be a foe to both of us, &s;hall there give place to friend&s;hip's &s;urer joys.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>How unfortunate it is that I have not yet been able to di&s;cover the place of her retreat!&mdash;I know not whom to apply to, for now I have no Harriet to inform me, &s;hould &s;he even be acquainted with it her&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can't you di&s;patch &s;ome per&s;on to learn in what manner &s;he left Sir Gregory's hou&s;e, and whither &s;he retired to?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stay, &s;tay; if I am not mi&s;taken, here comes one who can give us the be&s;t information&mdash;'tis &s;he&mdash;'tis Anna.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ANNA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Anna.</SPEAKER>
<P>O dear, good Mr. Belcour&mdash;pray Sir&mdash;a word if you plea&s;e.&mdash;But I beg this gentleman's pardon for be|ing &s;o bold.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Speak, Anna&mdash;how does Loui&s;a?&mdash;where is your mi&s;tre&s;s?&mdash;I have been &s;earching for her far and near, and was this moment lamenting that I had not been able to find out her retreat.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Anna.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, like enough; like enough&mdash;but times are &s;adly altered with us &s;ince you la&s;t &s;aw my lady at Sir
<PB N="38" REF="46">
Gregory's&mdash;but I &s;uppo&s;e, as you vi&s;it Mi&s;s Harriet every day, you know all about it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(confu&s;ed)</STAGE> Indeed I do not&mdash;nor have I been there lately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Anna.</SPEAKER>
<P>No!&mdash;Well, &s;ure that's wonderful&mdash;pray don't think me impertinent before this gentleman&mdash;but I hope you have a regard for that young lady, as I am &s;ure &s;he has for you; for I have often &s;een her &s;hed a power of tears, when my dear mi&s;tre&s;s only &s;aid it was po&s;&s;ible you might for&s;ake her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(confu&s;ed)</STAGE> Did &s;he indeed &s;hed tears?&mdash;But you don't an&s;wer our enquiries.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Anna.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, to be &s;ure, we have had a &s;ad change: and I know you wou'd pity my poor lady, and her &s;weet little boy too&mdash;if &s;he leaves him, I &s;hall be the only friend he has on earth; and my friend&s;hip, God help me! &s;ig|nifies little.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(emphatically)</STAGE> Where is the child?&mdash;bring me to him&mdash;while I live he &s;hall not want a father.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Anna.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, indeed, now you are very kind; for &s;omething my lady has ju&s;t heard determin'd her to leave this part of the country immediately.&mdash;She had, indeed, thought of taking a journey before, but now &s;he talks of never &s;eeing me again.&mdash;O Mr. Belcour! you and Mi&s;s Harriet were her friends&mdash;pray endeavour to prevent her going&mdash;I'm &s;ure I can never bear to part with &s;o kind and good a lady.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nor &s;hall you part with her, if my inter|ference can be of u&s;e.&mdash;My friend Lovele&s;s too &s;hall join his entreaties to mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Anna.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lovele&s;s!&mdash;&s;ure&punc; Sir, I think I have heard my lady mention &s;uch a name.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>My name!&mdash;heard your mi&s;tre&s;s mention my name!&mdash;impo&s;&s;ible&mdash;I never was in this country before.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Anna.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, then, perhaps I was mi&s;taken; for I have heard her mention it but once, to complain of &s;ome &s;uch
<PB N="39" REF="47">
per&s;on&mdash;I &s;uppo&s;e it was a relation who had u&s;ed her ill&mdash;for indeed &s;he has met with a great many enemies, and I am &s;ure &s;he never de&s;erv'd one.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let us then ha&s;te to re&s;cue her from further di&s;tre&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Anna.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! Sir!&mdash;you are very good&mdash;perhaps you have a lady and children of your own, that you love and cheri&s;h, and who have never known what it is to want a hu&s;band and a father.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(to Belcour)</STAGE> O, Belcour, what pang is &s;o &s;evere as artle&s;s nature's unde&s;ign'd rebuke?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, Anna, inform us where Loui&s;a re&s;ides, that we may endeavour to reconcile her to her fortune and her friends.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Anna.</SPEAKER>
<P>You'll find my poor lady at the white cottage, near Colonel Quorum's, by the wood-&s;ide; but (I a&s;k pardon for being &s;o bold) I am afraid my mi&s;tre&s;s will not chu&s;e to receive a vi&s;it from a &s;tranger, though &s;he may from Mr. Belcour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't be alarm'd, Anna&mdash;be a&s;&s;ured we will neither of us impertinently intrude&mdash;but I feel moved at her di&s;tre&s;s; exa&s;perated again&s;t the authors of it; and, as far as friend&s;hip allows, I am determined to protect her in|fant and her&s;elf. <STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">An apartment in <HI>LORD HECTIC'S</HI> Hou&s;e.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>LADY BETTY WORMWOOD,</HI> with a letter in her hand.</STAGE>
<P>Well, this is charming&mdash;who would have &s;u&s;pected it? Here have I found the copy of a love-letter addre&s;&s;ed to Colonel Quorum&mdash;from the prudent Mi&s;s Penelope Zodiac, who never de&s;cends to contemplate that impro|per
<PB N="40" REF="48">
creature, a man&mdash;It &s;eems an an&s;wer to one received from him.&mdash;The blooming maiden &s;corns heroics, and breathes her pa&s;&s;ion in the &s;imple language of nature.</P>
<STAGE>(Reads)</STAGE>
<LETTER>
<OPENER><SALUTE>Colonel Quorum,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>You reque&s;t an interview&mdash;can I refu&s;e it to a gentleman in whom I have ma$k'd an amiable repugnance towards the ordinary cla&s;s&punc; of females, and who&s;e conceptions, I am led to think, move in a higher &s;phere? Come, then, let us enjoy together a &s;cientific communion of &s;entiment, in a calm expo&s;ition of the nobler faculties.</P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED>Penelope Zodiac.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</LETTER>
<P>Well, here's the art of love turned into &s;cience, for the &s;ake of Colonel Quorum&mdash;one of the olde&s;t &s;cholars I know of. I dare &s;ay, now, if &s;he was here, &s;he would deny her own hand-writing. There's nothing I dete&s;t &s;o much, as &s;aying fir&s;t one thing and then another.&mdash;Here &s;he comes, a hypocritical creature.&mdash;My deare&s;t friend, I have been langui&s;hing for you this half hour.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mi&s;s</HI> PENELOPE ZODIAC.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>I too, my lady, have quitted my &s;tudies &s;ome time, in hopes to enjoy a little relaxed intercour&s;e. But <STAGE>(cautiou&s;ly)</STAGE> I hope we are not overheard&mdash;for, be|twixt our&s;elves, I have made a little di&s;covery that con|cerns you.&mdash;You know my talent&mdash;I had always a head for finding out &s;ecrets.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>True, Mi&s;s Penelope&mdash;I have a head for finding out &s;ecrets too&mdash;You indeed are too prudent to let any body di&s;cover your's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I believe no per&s;on is more di&s;|creet&mdash;but to the point&mdash;You mu&s;t know then, my dear Lady Betty, that odious woman, that Loui&s;a, on being
<PB N="41" REF="49">
di&s;mi&s;&s;ed from Sir Gregory's, has had the confidence to &s;eat her&s;elf by Colonel Quorum.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>By Colonel Quorum!&mdash;Ah! I &s;uppo&s;e &s;he thought her&s;elf &s;afe by the &s;ide of ju&s;tice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>But &s;he &s;hall find her&s;elf mi&s;taken&mdash;<HI>You</HI> &s;hall not be impo&s;ed upon in that manner.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>I impo&s;ed upon, Mi&s;s Pen!&mdash;Don't be unea&s;y on that head&mdash;believe me, I &s;ee through the whole de&s;ign.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be&s;ides too, the Colonel is a mighty good &s;ort of a man, and &s;hould not be led a&s;tray by &s;o artful a minx as &s;he is.&mdash;I cannot help di&s;liking her, merely on your account.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>I perceive you can't&mdash;and am exceedingly obliged to you for the warmth you expre&s;s merely <HI>on my account:</HI> but, though you wi&s;h me to be apprehen&s;ive for Colonel Quorum, upon my word I don't &s;ee the nece&s;&s;ity for it, as I dare &s;ay he has not the lea&s;t regard for any female living.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not of a light &s;ort, I dare be &s;worn&mdash;though I cannot believe he would be in&s;en&s;ible to proper attractions&mdash;<Q>&startq;&endq;a prudent, re&s;erved manner, and a &s;cien|tific mind.&mdash;But, after all, who knows what this for|ward hu&s;&s;ey may do?</Q></P>
</SP>
<Q>&startq;&endq;

<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>True, indeed; &s;hould &s;he venture to write to him, &s;he might con&s;ent to an interview&mdash;but that is not likely&mdash;No woman, you know, Mi&s;s Pen. could po&s;&s;ibly think of writing to a man for &s;uch a purpo&s;e.</P>
</SP></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>"Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(&s;mothering her vexation)</STAGE> Aye&mdash;<Q>&startq;why yes, writing to a gentleman, as you &s;ay, with improper ideas&mdash;no lady could think of.&endq;</Q>&mdash;I hope &s;he knows nothing of my letter. <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I was certain you would agree with me&mdash;however the Colonel, I believe, might be tru&s;ted:
<PB N="42" REF="50">
I dare &s;ay he would laugh at any woman that was guilty of &s;uch an indi&s;cretion&mdash;don't you think he would?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Laugh! why, no.&mdash;I mean&mdash;yes, cer|tainly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord, Mi&s;s Penelope, what is the matter? You &s;eem intere&s;ted about the Colonel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>I intere&s;ted about a man! Heaven for|bid! I was only thinking of that Jezabel.&mdash;As for the Colonel, I believe he has too ju&s;t notions of what is beco|ming, for your Mi&s;s to &s;poil.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Mi&s;s, Mi&s;s Penelope! You know I hate Mi&s;&s;es&mdash;your Colonel, I apprehend you would &s;ay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mine, Lady Betty! I beg you would not in&s;inuate that I have a Colonel, or that I would quit the &s;ublime meditations for any Colonel upon earth; therefore, Ma'am, I in&s;i&s;t upon it you will not Colonel me. <STAGE>(walks about in a pa&s;&s;ion)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Ma'am, I beg ten thou&s;and pardons.&mdash;Indeed I could not have imagined I &s;hould have affected you &s;o much&mdash;and, had I known your attachment to Colonel Quorum, I am &s;ure I &s;hould have been the la&s;t per&s;on in the world to have mentioned it&mdash;for I hate be|ing ill-natured, you know I do.&mdash;I am glad I have pu|ni&s;hed her hypocri&s;y. <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LOVELESS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ladies, may I intreat permi&s;&s;ion to intrude?&mdash;I come in behalf of di&s;tre&s;s, to plead a female cau&s;e, and &s;ue to you for pity:&mdash;I am told, Lady Betty, you know the unfortunate Loui&s;a, and are not ignorant of what &s;he has &s;uffered from your brother's pur&s;uits. Might I reque&s;t you to be her friend?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Her friend! <HI>Me</HI> to be her friend! Indeed I dete&s;t ill-nature, and never &s;ay an unkind word of any
<PB N="43" REF="51">
body&mdash;otherwi&s;e I could not &s;uppo&s;e you would have a&s;ked me &s;uch a thing for &s;o worthle&s;s an object;&mdash;I am not, however, the per&s;on to expo&s;e my own &s;ex, though, to be &s;ure&mdash;one cannot help making di&s;tinctions.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Lady Betty! And it is tho&s;e cruel di&s;|tinctions, which they who have fortunately never tran&s;|gre&s;&s;ed are too apt to make, that bar the entrance of virtuous &s;ociety, and cut off the faint hope of repentant error. But here, I under&s;tand, there is no cau&s;e for this &s;everity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>O to be &s;ure not, Mr. Lovele&s;s! And &s;o you think there is no occa&s;ion for ladies to know any thing of erudition, and logarithms, and trigonometry&mdash;they need do nothing but go about making love, and dreaming of the &s;en&s;ations&mdash;oh fie!&mdash;If &s;he does not know how a lady ought to conduct her&s;elf properly, let her read Plutarch's Lives.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, Madam, if I am rightly informed, the conduct of Loui&s;a is not &s;o reproachable.&mdash;Nay, Madam, I am told there is a very re&s;pectable gentleman in the neighbourhood, a Colonel Quorum, who has made her an offer of his hand.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(alarmed, and attempting to conceal it)</STAGE> Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(a&s;toni&s;hed)</STAGE> Really!&mdash;Colonel Quorum offer her his hand!&mdash;Well, if &s;ome people can forget what others have done, and treat them like proper people, for my part I never can be ill-natured enough not to rejoice at it.&mdash;And I dare &s;ay Mi&s;s Penelope Zodiac will be en|tirely of my opinion. <STAGE>(&s;neering)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray&mdash;Mr. Lovele&s;s&mdash;Sir&mdash;I really &s;peak out of regard for the lady&mdash;what was the re&s;ult of it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>As I under&s;tand, Madam, &s;he civilly and mode&s;tly declined it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="44" REF="52">
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h &s;he had taken him at his word.&mdash;I &s;peak out of regard to the lady too&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>On this account then, though perhaps in an inferior &s;ituation, &s;he is entitled to every re&s;pect.&mdash;If Lord Hectic therefore has an unconquerable pa&s;&s;ion, why not ri&s;e above common prejudices, and make her an offer of his hand!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir!&mdash;My brother make Loui&s;a an offer of his hand!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(turning to her)</STAGE> And really, Lady Betty, as my Lord is &s;uch a libertine&mdash;I mention it for the &s;ake of his morals&mdash;I do not think he can do better than reform by marriage.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>And pray, Mi&s;s Penelope, who made you a judge, as an unmarried lady, of marriage, and refor|mation?&mdash;You, who&s;e head is alwaysamong the poles?&mdash;You &s;hould not find fault, I am &s;ure, who&s;e di&s;po&s;ition is &s;o much in the milky way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord, Lady Betty! I believe I find fault as little as other ladies, who know no more of delicacy and metaphy&s;ics than the Great Mogul.&mdash;A widow, a mere widow!&mdash;"next kin to an impure." <STAGE>(walking about angrily.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ladies, I beg ten thou&s;and pardons&mdash;I really had no intention of offending; and am exceedingly con|cern'd to &s;ee you both &s;o angry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Angry, Mr. Lovele&s;s! I don't know what you mean!&mdash;I can a&s;&s;ure you I am not angry&mdash;not at all angry; but I know when to be di&s;plea&s;ed, as well as other people.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>And you, Mi&s;s Zodiac&mdash;your philo&s;ophy at lea&s;t&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>&mdash;Pray, Sir, don't tantalize me&mdash;I know when a lady ought to be a philo&s;opher, and when &s;he ought to lay her philo&s;ophy a&s;ide.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="$5" REF="53">
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, Lady Betty&mdash;&s;hould Lord Hectic him&s;elf be inclined to marry her&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg, Sir, you will put no &s;uch indecency into his head.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Col. Quorum has ab&s;olutely offer'd him&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Impo&s;&s;ible!&mdash;I am &s;ure he has a better ta&s;te for the &s;ublime and beautiful.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>A peer of the realm give his hand to a wanton!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>A &s;oldier di&s;grace his arms with an ignoramus!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let me entreat you, ladies, to be more candid.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Some folks are always intermeddling where they have no bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, endeavouring to &s;teer, without knowing a point of the compa&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Impertinent intru&s;ion!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Totally in the dark, as to the effect of cau&s;es.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, ladies, I have done&mdash;I came hither to appeal to your tenderne&s;s, not to awaken your re&s;ent|ment.&mdash;I &s;imply imagin'd the misfortunes of an unhappy woman wou'd have found an advocate in every female brea&s;t&mdash;but I am now convinc'd that pride is far &s;uperior to humanity, and &s;cience &s;oars too high to have any know|ledge of the trifling feelings of nature.&mdash;Ladies, your obedient. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Meddling creature!&mdash;I wi&s;h he was mar|ried a &s;econd time, for his pains.&mdash;My dear friend, Mi&s;s Penelope, that the men &s;hould imagine they could pro|voke us!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>True, my dear friend, Lady Betty&mdash;I do flatter my&s;elf that a knowledge of the &s;pheres, and an
<PB N="46" REF="54">
in&s;ight into the heavenly motions, prevent me from all earthly provocations at lea&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly&mdash;I knew you cou'd not be &s;o ignorant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I was &s;ure you cou'd not be ill|natured.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>I never could be ill-natured in my life&mdash;So let's lo&s;e no time in contriving &s;ome how or other to ruin this trouble&s;ome woman, and drive her out of the neighbourhood. <STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">A Room hung with Maps, old Pedigrees, and Coats of Arms, with an old Banner over them, in Sir <HI>Gregory</HI>'s Hou&s;e.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>LORD HECTIC</HI> ha&s;tily, the Captain following after|wards; Sir <HI>GREGORY</HI> with one Hand behind him, the other up to his No&s;e&mdash;at a &s;low &s;olemn &s;tep.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't make any excu&s;es to me, Sir Gregory;&mdash;you a courtier, and forget what is due to a peer, and a man of con&s;equence!&mdash;Heh' Captain?</P>
<STAGE>(turning to Swagger, who keeps at his back.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye&mdash;who has a captain to back him be|fore and behind.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>A man of nice feelings, and &s;trong powers. <STAGE>(coughing)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be calm, my Lord&mdash;pray be calm&mdash;and a little more ceremonious, if you plea&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't talk to me of c$lmne&s;s and cere|mony&mdash;don't you &s;ee that I'm in a violent pa&s;&s;ion&mdash;Heh' heh'!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>O fait, and &s;o am I, my dear&mdash;without any ceremony at all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>It can't be, my Lord&mdash;the thing is im|po&s;&s;ible&mdash;a peer can't be in a pa&s;&s;ion&mdash;never was &s;uch a
<PB N="47" REF="55">
thing heard of, except in the Hou&s;e; there, indeed, vio|lence is a virtue, and he may &s;ay any thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't tell me of &s;aying any thing&mdash;when I am ab&s;olutely dumb at your incivility, Sir Gre|gory.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>I guilty of incivility!&mdash;Place and prece|dence, my Lord&mdash;but it is impo&s;&s;ible.&mdash;Beau Na&s;h him|&s;elf dur&s;t not have made &s;uch a charge.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>O' my con&s;cience then, you call turning a lady out of your hou&s;e no incivility at all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>What &s;ay you to that, Sir Gregory?&mdash;do you think Beau Na&s;h wou'd have done &s;o?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q>&startq;&endq;Fie, my Lord&mdash;the old court never cared who was turned out.&mdash;I &s;hould blu&s;h to &s;ee your lord&s;hip unea&s;y at the di&s;mi&s;&s;ion of any thing under a maid of honour&mdash;and they are not what they u&s;ed to be neither.</Q></P>
</SP>
<Q>&startq;&endq;

<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;ha! Sir Gregory, don't plague me about old maids of honour; give me a modern one&mdash;hem!&mdash;but have you no re&s;pect for the affections of a man of fa&s;hion?</P>
</SP></Q>
<Q>&startq;&endq;

<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly nothing plea&s;es me more than to &s;ee a man of fa&s;hion in love, in a gallant and gentleman-like manner. But then I expect forms; no clande&s;tine vi&s;its in my hou&s;e. When a proper equi|page is prepared&mdash;a number of out-riders&mdash;with an avant-courier&mdash;his lord&s;hip's chaplain attending&mdash;due notice given&mdash;and approbation a&s;ked&mdash;no man more ready in his place than Sir Gregory Glovetop&mdash;at the head of the great &s;tairs, in point ruffles and clock'd &s;tockings.</P>
</SP></Q>
<Q>&startq;&endq;

<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>What the devil, did&s;t thou expect that I &s;hould have vi&s;ited a lady with a dozen out-riders and a chaplain? acquainted all my &s;ervants that I had a
<PB N="48" REF="56">
love affair upon my hands, <STAGE>(coughing)</STAGE> and brought my whole hou&s;ehold to partake of it?</P>
</SP></Q>
<Q>&startq;&endq;

<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>O yes; Sir Gregory thinks there can't be too many to partake of a good thing.</P>
</SP></Q>
<Q>&startq;&endq;

<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be&s;ides, did&s;t thou imagine a beautiful creature would not be plea&s;ed with a private meeting,&mdash;There's nothing the women are &s;o fond of as &s;e|crets.</P>
</SP></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>"Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord, <Q>there &s;hould be no &s;ecrets &startq;out of the cabinet; and there indeed&mdash;but I am &s;ilent.&endq;</Q> Pray, gentlemen, be cool&mdash;If Sir Clement was alive, he could only a&s;k pardon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>And don't you expect that I &s;hould lay &s;uch a piece of family ruins in a&s;hes, as a puni&s;hment for your audacity?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord, I hope you will not forget your rank.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, fait, and I have no rank to forget&mdash;So as you have been &s;o rude to the young lady, be civil to the gentleman, and give us &s;atisfaction immediately. <STAGE>(ad|$ancing nearer)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>I could not break through forms for the univer&s;e.&mdash;Single combat, to be &s;ure, may be maintained, but always with proper decorum. You &s;tate your grie|vances&mdash;I reply&mdash;preliminaries are broken&mdash;and then war is declared in due cour&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Devil burn me, but we'll do as the French do&mdash;declare war without &s;aying a &s;yllable of the matter. So come on, Sir Gregory&mdash;By St. Patrick, I'll bother both &s;ides of your ears with nothing but war! war! <STAGE>(bel|lowing).</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> COLONEL QUORUM.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Peace, I &s;ay, or I'll read the riot act&mdash;
<PB N="49" REF="57">
Gentlemen, your mo&s;t obedient.&mdash;And now, what is the matter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>The matter is, Colonel, that I believe your coming has &s;aved my life&mdash;though I cannot ap prove of this entrance into my hou&s;e without ceremony, for all that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>What &s;ignifies how we came into the hou&s;e, when you've turned out the mo&s;t beautiful&mdash;the mo&s;t exqui&s;ite&mdash;hem! hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know it all&mdash;the mo&s;t accompli&s;h'd Loui&s;a.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure, Colonel:&mdash;Egad, I thought you had ta&s;te enough to be of my opinion.&mdash;What a charming appendage &s;he would have made in the &s;uite of a man of fa&s;hion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(a&s;toni&s;hed)</STAGE> My Lord!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, &s;he would have been a very &s;weet appendage to us all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Love, Colonel, without the galling chains of marriage&mdash;a companion for the time being, and a temporary addition to my dome&s;tic joys&mdash;hem! hem!&mdash;be&s;ides, &s;he &s;hould have retired on a pen&s;ion from the fatigues of gallantry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, by my knighthood, nobody could have &s;aid that but a courtier.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>And is it po&s;&s;ible that you can be talking about the divine Loui&s;a in this manner?&mdash;I &s;wear that &s;he is purer than innocence it&s;elf.&mdash;Death and de&s;o|lation! was it you, Sir Gregory, who &s;aid any thing to the prejudice of Loui&s;a's character?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>I talk of character, and bred at court, Colonel! how could you imagine &s;uch a thing? I who was always called Anti-Scandal by the ladies of the bed|chamber.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="50" REF="58">
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, zounds, Sir! I &s;uppo&s;e it was you who dared to hold an opinion to the prejudice of the mo&s;t charming of her &s;ex.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>O! by no means.&mdash;Upon my &s;houl, and I have no opinion of her at all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then you alone, my Lord, mu&s;t an|&s;wer for this defamation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not I, indeed; I never an&s;wer for any thing.&mdash;To be &s;ure, I do think her hand&s;ome&mdash;hem! hem!&mdash;as every man of gallantry ought&mdash;and may have paid her a few little attentions, perfectly innocent as yet.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>By Heaven I believe &s;o&mdash;but men of your lord&s;hip's turn are apt to forget, that in the eyes of the &s;ober part of the world, tho&s;e innocent attentions have the appearance of criminality, and the offer of them is &s;ometimes as fatal as the &s;ucce&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very &s;ententious and moral, egad!&mdash;but really, Colonel, do you expect that a man of fa&s;hion, in the heyday of youth and &s;pirits&mdash;hem! hem!&mdash;as I am, can be &s;topt, in his pur&s;uit of beauty, by a lecture on morality?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>A lecture on blood and vengeance, my Lord!&mdash;for know, when tho&s;e pur&s;uits happen to be directed again&s;t the innocence which boa&s;ts a protector, balls and bombardments! that protection which my arm affords her mu&s;t fir&s;t be defeated.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(&s;talking about)</STAGE> I &s;wear, by Sir Philip Sydney, the old court reviv'd again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>A challenge, as I'm a peer!&mdash;hem! hem!&mdash;but I take no advantages, Colonel; and for once you &s;hall e&s;cape being brought upon your knees before the Hou&s;e for a breach of privilege.&mdash;The Captain, however, lays under no &s;uch impediment; and, being a plebeian quarrel, may enter into it with propriety.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="51" REF="59">
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(advancing to the Captain)</STAGE> Well, Sir, what have you to &s;ay?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my &s;oul, Colonel, nothing at all: the very &s;ight of a ju&s;tice always binds me over to keep the peace.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord&mdash;I blu&s;h to think that a no|bleman, who dares wantonly &s;port with the character of a woman, &s;hould tremble to defend what he is not afraid to a&s;&s;ert.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't provoke me, Colonel&mdash;I'm a very pa&s;&s;ionate man, I a&s;&s;ure you.&mdash;Stand between us, Captain Swagger.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not I, my Lord&mdash;I'm a very pa&s;&s;ion$te man too.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Contemptible eva&s;ion!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray don't irritate me any longer&mdash;I really may forget my rank.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds and the devil!&mdash;my lord chief ju&s;tice him&s;elf would be forced to &s;wear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(interpo&s;ing)</STAGE> Pray, Colonel, be patient: con&s;ider what privileges noblemen are entitled to.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come along, Captain&mdash;I'm indifferent about my&s;elf; you, however, have been ill treated, and I'll think of your wrongs with proper re&s;entment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fait, and that's very kind&mdash;but, if your $ord&s;hip plea&s;es, we'll forget them both as &s;oon as we can. Mind, Colonel, if I &s;hould remember this treat|ment&mdash;I bear no malice, becau&s;e I told you I had forgot|ten it. <STAGE>[Exeunt both.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bravo, Colonel! A &s;econd Marlborough, as I live.&mdash;No one enemy dare &s;tand before you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't know that, Sir Gregory.&mdash;Can I call tho&s;e my friends who have treated Loui&s;a un|kindly? and are not you in that number? A lady for whom I have the mo&s;t profound regard, and who I have
<PB N="52" REF="60">
&s;ome rea&s;on to think&mdash;but no matter.&mdash;However I did expect you would&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't expect me, Colonel, to negotiate any private treaties; I mu&s;t be public amba&s;&s;ador, or nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>So you &s;hall&mdash;&s;o you &s;hall&mdash;and pray lo&s;e no time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't hurry me&punc;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(impetuou&s;ly)</STAGE> Zounds, Sir Gregory&mdash;fly this in&s;tant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(calmly)</STAGE> Can't fly&mdash;no air balloon ex|ploits for me. <STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<TRAILER>END OF THE THIRD ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<PB N="53" REF="61">
<HEAD>ACT IV.</HEAD>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">A Wood. <HI>LOUISA'S</HI> Cottage at a Di&s;tance.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>LOUISA</HI> in a great agitation, looking back as &s;he advances.</STAGE>
<P>'TIS impo&s;&s;ible!&mdash;It could not be Lovele&s;s, that I di&s;covered ju&s;t now in the wood&mdash;ba&s;e, per|fidious man!&mdash;cruelly as he has treated me, he wou'd not come hither to in&s;ult the mi&s;ery he has occa&s;ioned.&mdash;No, 'tis not in nature to be &s;o inhuman;&mdash;be&s;ides, he is wholly ignorant of my &s;ituation.&mdash;<Q>&startq;My eyes have cer|tainly deceiv'd me; and my tortur'd mind, &s;till &s;adly bent on former &s;cenes, pictures re&s;emblances where none exi&s;t.&mdash;Yes, dear fatal copy <HI>(taking out a picture)</HI> of him who once po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ed my virgin heart; in who&s;e fal&s;e bo&s;om all my fonde&s;t hopes were centered; and who&s;e delu&s;ive form, in &s;pite of all my wrongs, I can|not tear from my remembrance&mdash;let me examine thee again.&endq;</Q>&mdash;Whoever he was, he &s;eem'd, as I thought, in earne&s;t di&s;cour&s;e with Mr. Belcour&mdash;they are not yet come out from the wood&mdash;I'll endeavour to &s;teal &s;oftly through the thicket unob&s;erved, and get a nearer view.</P>
<STAGE>[Retiring a moment.</STAGE>
<STAGE>(Re-enter with a quick pace.)</STAGE>
<P>Ah! whither &s;hall I run?&mdash;'Tis he! 'tis the barbarous, unrelenting &s;poiler.&mdash;Oh! unfeeling Lovele&s;s!&mdash;After having invaded the innocence of my youth; driven me from my native, peaceful home; deprived me of a fa|ther's fond protection; and expo&s;ed me, and your help|le&s;s
<PB N="54" REF="62">
infant, to all the mi&s;eries of want and &s;hame, of per|&s;ecution and contempt&mdash;you come, to complete the mea|&s;ure of your guilt, to rob us of the only little &s;hed that's left us; to triumph o'er our complicated woes, and &s;port with agony unutterable.&mdash;Ye gracious Powers! to what am I reduc'd!&mdash;My poor brain will turn.&mdash;<Q>&startq;But per|haps I do him inju&s;tice,&mdash;perhaps he feels.&mdash;O! no; I will not &s;ee him&mdash;I will not endure his pity&mdash;when I mu&s;t de&s;pi&s;e his heart. <STAGE>(Starts.)</STAGE> Heavens!&mdash;he advances&mdash;where, where &s;hall I retreat to?&mdash;Alas! the world affords me now no place to hide in!&endq;</Q>&mdash;I'll fly then&mdash;beg, &s;tarve, do any thing, rather than bear the pre&s;ence of a man I ought for ever to dete&s;t&mdash;<STAGE>(Runs, looking back, then &s;tops)</STAGE> but &s;ee, they &s;eparate; and Mr. Belcour approaches alone.&mdash;I will endeavour to compo&s;e my&s;elf&mdash;&s;hou'd he be informed of my &s;ituation, he will have learned, at lea&s;t, that intentional guilt has never cau&s;ed the&s;e tears to flow.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> BELCOUR.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Forgive, Madam, my freedom, in thus break|ing in upon your retirement: but let me hope the motive may plead for its excu&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(he&s;itating)</STAGE> Mr. Belcour's conduct, I flatter my&s;elf, will never need excu&s;e. I thought I &s;aw you with another gentleman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Madam, with my friend, Mr. Lovele&s;s.&mdash;He wanted much to offer his good &s;ervices; but, being a &s;tranger, wou'd not venture &s;o far without permi&s;&s;ion; he has therefore retired for the pre&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am ea&s;y again. <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>&mdash;Mr. Belcour, I thank you for your attention&mdash;but, at pre&s;ent, &s;olitude is what I &s;eek for.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am aware, Madam, you may feel a re|pugnance in committing your cares to one &s;o little con|nected with you as my&s;elf&mdash;but be a&s;&s;ured, tho' only an acquaintance, I feel all the &s;ympathy of friend&s;hip; and,
<PB N="55" REF="63">
knowing the &s;tory of your griefs, wi&s;h &s;incerely to remove them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(alarm'd)</STAGE> Then I am lo&s;t indeed! <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> What, Sir, has the gentleman, Mr. Lovele&s;s&mdash;has he communicated any thing?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Lovele&s;s communicated, Madam!&mdash;my friend Lovele&s;s, as a man of probity and feeling, is, in|deed, intere&s;ted in your cau&s;e;&mdash;but he knows your &s;uf|ferings only from report, nor has he communicated any thing that can give you unea&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg pardon, Mr. Belcour, for the &s;uppo|&s;ition.&mdash;But I know the ill-nature of the world, and I thought &s;omething might have been &s;aid&mdash;that the gentle|man you were with might&mdash;but perhaps I am mi&s;|taken.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, Madam, if you knew my friend as I do&mdash;were you acquainted with the goodne&s;s of his heart, and the tenderne&s;s of his nature, you would be &s;en&s;ible of the high opinion he entertains of your de&s;ert.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hold my&s;elf obliged for the good opinion of every one.&mdash;But, Sir, we find our&s;elves &s;ometimes de|ceived&mdash;appearances are not&mdash;however it is not for me to be intere&s;ted about it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Believe me, he reprobates Lord Hectic's con|duct as much as my&s;elf; and both of us feel for the in|convenience it has &s;ubjected you to.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>O Mr. Belcour! I have too long walked hand in hand with &s;orrow, to feel much concern for any incon|venience;&mdash;Lord Hectic has been trouble&s;ome to me, I own, but he is not the man that I am mo&s;t apprehen&s;ive of.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, Madam, a&s;&s;ure your&s;elf I am your friend&mdash;I &s;ee Lord Hectic's conduct has involved you in di&s;tre&s;s;&mdash;indeed I blu&s;h for the unworthine&s;s of his &s;en|timents.&mdash;Allow me the ta&s;k of undeceiving him as to
<PB N="56" REF="64">
your character, and $onvincing him of the impropriety of his pur&s;uits.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Belcour, if my Lord Hectic's &s;entiments were an object of con&s;ideration, there is no one I would more gladly employ in that ta&s;k than your&s;elf;&mdash;to be &s;ure every woman of &s;en&s;ibility mu&s;t feel for injurious &s;u&s;pi|cions;&mdash;but I have learned the le&s;&s;on of &s;ubmi&s;&s;ion; and, while I thank you for your attention, Sir, believe me when I a&s;&s;ure you my di&s;tre&s;&s;es are of &s;uch a nature, that even your kindne&s;s can give me no relief.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure, Madam, my fortune at pre&s;ent is narrow, tho' my good wi&s;hes towards you are unbound|ed;&mdash;but I am certain Mr. Lovele&s;s, who&s;e mind is en|larged as his circum&s;tances are ample, will gladly &s;upply every deficiency.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Excu&s;e me, Sir&mdash;want of fortune is not what I allude to;&mdash;but were it &s;o, and rigid penury now &s;tared me in the face,&mdash;nothing &s;hou'd induce me to apply there for &s;uccour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Were you acquainted with my friend, I am certain you wou'd alter your opinion;&mdash;his de&s;ire to &s;erve you is founded on the noble&s;t principles,&mdash;for he is a man, Madam, who, &s;oftened by misfortunes of his own, is alive only to the calamity of others.&mdash;He has conver&s;ed with your &s;ervant Anna; has &s;een your little boy, is charmed with his artle&s;s looks and infant prattle; and has commi&s;&s;ioned me to reque&s;t you would commit the care of his youth, and the e&s;tabli&s;hment of his fortune, to his protection and regard.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did he take notice of my boy?&mdash;O nature, how powerful is thy force!&mdash;The mother at this moment almo&s;t cancels all the pa&s;t <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>&mdash;Exeu&s;e the&s;e tears, Sir;&mdash;a parent's grateful tribute for her only child.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Madam, your &s;on too was equally &s;truck with his attention&mdash;&s;at on his knee, threw his
<PB N="57" REF="65">
little arms about his neck&mdash;embraced him&mdash;called him fa|ther, and &s;aid that you wou'd thank him for them both.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>O Sir!&mdash;Your de&s;cription is more than I can &s;upport.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shall I bring Mr. Lovele&s;s to you, Madam? I can ea&s;ily overtake him, and he will repeat in per&s;on the &s;entiments that do honour to his heart. <STAGE>(going.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, no, Sir&mdash;not for the world&mdash;I cou'd not bear it.&mdash;For my&s;elf, my &s;ojourn here will be but &s;hort&mdash;for my child, tell him 'tis his&mdash;I bequeath him to his care: may he regard him with a parent's fondne&s;s, and may my boy return it with a filial duty!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>HARRIET</HI> behind.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Loui&s;a in clo&s;e conference with Mr. Belcour!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Re&s;t a&s;&s;ured, Madam, that your intere&s;t will always be near my heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE> Heavens! what do I hear?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(weeping.)</STAGE> Forgive, Mr. Belcour, that af|fliction which my &s;ituation naturally produces;&mdash;I mu&s;t leave this place for ever&mdash;I feel too for Harriet, I know &s;he loves me, and I fear her gentle heart will break&mdash;in|deed I am grateful for your attentions; but it is on a &s;ub|ject on which you will not take it ami&s;s if I endeavour to conceal my tears. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>I conjure you, Madam, to allow me&mdash;to hear me. By Heaven there is a &s;omething in that woman that intere&s;ts me&mdash;I mu&s;t follow her, and endeavour to per&s;uade her to look for happier days. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(coming forward)</STAGE> Can I believe my &s;en&s;es?&mdash;can that be Loui&s;a?&mdash;the partner of my bo&s;om, who &s;har'd my confidence&mdash;to who&s;e &s;orrows I gave all my pity?&mdash;This then was the &s;tory &s;he could not reveal to me without blu&s;hing; well might &s;he avoid my en|quiries&mdash;the cau&s;e of Belcour's unkind letter to me is now
<PB N="58" REF="66">
fully explained;&mdash;Loui&s;a was the &s;acrifice he could not make&mdash;ah! treacherous friend! If &s;uch is the treatment we are to expect from tho&s;e we mo&s;t e&s;teem, where &s;hall our affections be placed? <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">An Apartment in <HI>LORD HECTIC'S</HI> Hou&s;e.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter Lady <HI>BETTY WORMWOOD,</HI> followed by <HI>JANUS.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>But now, my dear Mr. Janus, you know my regard for propriety; and therefore, notwith&s;tanding I cannot help feeling for the unhappy wretches of my own &s;ex, yet we mu&s;t have this creature, who has capti|vated my brother's affections, removed out of the neigh|bourhood, no matter how, and I &s;hall depend upon your ingenuity for doing it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(bowing)</STAGE> True, my Lady&mdash;Burn, in his chap|ter about nui&s;ances, does mention the women; but I don't recollect he &s;ays they can be removed whether they will or no&mdash;can your Lady&s;hip remember a ca&s;e in point?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pooh! Mr. Janus, how &s;hould I remem|ber ca&s;es?&mdash;I want your a&s;&s;i&s;tance; and you mu&s;t &s;tretch a point as far as you can, to oblige me.&mdash;The law, you know, is a wide field.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is &s;o, my Lady&mdash;it is &s;o&mdash;and I don't mind going a little about the edges of it;&mdash;but totally to tre&s;|pa&s;s might put me upon the Black Li&s;t.&mdash;However, I'll look into the Attorney's Guide, and &s;ee what I can do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, come, Mr. Janus, I know you are a man of integrity, and hone&s;t people have their &s;cruples;&mdash;but here is the attorney's guide&mdash;take and examine it <STAGE>(giving him a pur&s;e);</STAGE>&mdash;and tho' you &s;hould act a little again&s;t <STAGE>(he puts out his hand to take it)</STAGE> the letter, yet, in equity, you wou'd undoubtedly be ju&s;tified.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="59" REF="67">
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, to be &s;ure, your lady&s;hip has &s;et the matter in a new light.&mdash;I had forgot equity totally;&mdash;and really I can't help &s;eeing it now in the light of a con|&s;piracy again&s;t your brother.&mdash;I remember a ca&s;e in the rebellion of forty-five&mdash;John Jones ver&s;us Sandy Maclean&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(interrupting)</STAGE> True, true, good Mr. Janus&mdash;I perceive you begin to feel the weight of my argument&mdash;it certainly is a con&s;piracy again&s;t my bro|ther's per&s;on, as well as his fortune; and therefore &s;he mu&s;t on no account be &s;uffered to come near his hou&s;e.&mdash;I think you &s;ee the ca&s;e ju&s;t as you &s;hould do&mdash;do me the favour of accepting this <STAGE>(gives a bank note).</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(taking it)</STAGE> Yes, yes, my Lady&mdash;I know where to put my finger; and you may re&s;t a&s;&s;ured, on the faith of an attorney, the plaintiff &s;hall be non&s;uited, and her cau&s;e kicked out of court&mdash;&s;he &s;hall never get into my Lord's hou&s;e whil&s;t I live, and in two days &s;he &s;hall be fifty miles from the place.&mdash;But hold, my Lady&mdash;there is one difficulty has ju&s;t &s;truck me&mdash;there is another attorney in the pari&s;h&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Mr. Janus,&mdash;what of that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, my Lady, I think we had better have him likewi&s;e. Two of us, I think, will fini&s;h the bu&s;i|ne&s;s.&mdash;Suppo&s;e your Lady&s;hip gives me his retaining fee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, Mr. Janus&mdash;only &s;pare my feelings, and get the jade removed by fair or foul means, and I &s;han't mind a little expence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! my Lady, two attornies!&mdash;only think of that, and you need not de&s;pair of any means whatever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Soft&mdash;I &s;ee my brother coming this way&mdash;you mu&s;t not mention my having been here for the world, or the &s;ubject of our di&s;cour&s;e&mdash;only remember the bu&s;ine&s;s. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="60" REF="68">
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, depend upon me&mdash;as I have mad$ &s;ure of the principal evidence. <STAGE>(pocketing the pur&s;e)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LORD HECTIC.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! my little attorney! what the devil art thou pocketing there &s;o ha&s;tily&mdash;thy con&s;cience?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(confu&s;ed)</STAGE> No, my Lord, no&mdash;thank Heaven, I am not a&s;hamed of my con&s;cience&mdash;I only took the liberty of &s;tepping in to enquire after your Lord&s;hip's health&mdash;I am delighted to &s;ee you look &s;o charmingly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>I dare &s;ay thou art&mdash;e&s;pecially as thou wilt get nothing by my death.&mdash;But thou art come mo&s;t luckily, my little vellum-blotter&mdash;for I want thy a&s;&s;i&s;t|ance;&mdash;thou know'&s;t the woman I was mentioning to thee the other day&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, my Lord, the lady that was at Sir Gregory Glovetop's&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>The &s;ame&mdash;hem! hem!&mdash;the thought of her warms me. Now I am told &s;he is about to leave this country immediately&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Really, my Lord&mdash;I am prodigiou&s;ly &s;orry for it.&mdash;This is lucky!&mdash;I &s;hall carry her lady&s;hip's cau&s;e without bringing it to a trial. <STAGE>(A&s;ide)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, as &s;uch a circum&s;tance would anni|hilate my hopes, that mu&s;t be prevented immediately; and therefore thou mu&s;t exert all thy ingenuity to keep her in the neighbourhood&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord! to be &s;ure, if your Lord&s;hip wi&s;hes it; but how can an attorney prevent a lady from follow|ing her inclinations?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, you mu&s;t know, on her leaving that old fool, Sir Gregory, &s;he has become, without know|ing it, tenant to a little cottage of mine, which I learned this morning from my &s;teward&mdash;and therefore, on &s;ome pretence or other, I would have &s;uch difficulties thrown
<PB N="61" REF="69">
in the way, as may prevent her putting her de&s;ign in execution.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye&mdash;payment of rent; which, being an ex|ceeding neat hou&s;e, may be exorbitant&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>True&mdash;then &s;he may perhaps think of a per&s;onal application to me&mdash;I &s;tep in, and become her guardian angel at once.&mdash;You take the matter, heh?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I remember a ca&s;e&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damn your ca&s;es&mdash;pocket that <STAGE>(throws a pur&s;e)</STAGE> and fly to execute my plan.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(going, and returns)</STAGE> I do.&mdash;She &s;hall be &s;afe in your Lord&s;hip's hou&s;e in le&s;s than two hours&mdash;but, my Lord, the ladies of a family you know are a little in|qui&s;itive, &s;ometimes&mdash;Now, as I have the honour of tran&s;acting bu&s;ine&s;s for your Lord&s;hip's &s;i&s;ter, I hope &s;he will not know a &s;yllable of what I undertake for your Lord&s;hip&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! I &s;ee thou art an hone&s;t fellow, and &s;tand up for thy character.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do&mdash;I do, my Lord&mdash;My father always &s;aid I was too hone&s;t to thrive.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>In your profe&s;&s;ion he meant&mdash;but hold, is not there another hone&s;t gentleman of your calling in this pari&s;h?&mdash;You mu&s;t take care that Loui&s;a gets no ad|vice about our proceedings&mdash;for I do not imagine they will be &s;trictly legal.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never fear him, I have him under my thumb here. <STAGE>(putting his hand on his pocket)</STAGE>&mdash;Be&s;ides, the gentle|men in our way are very honourable, and never betray each other.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then there's that fighting Colonel mu&s;t be taken care of, for he's too honourable by half&mdash;and is &s;uch an old fool, that he actually wants to marry her, with his infirm con&s;titution&mdash;Hem! hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Does he &s;o?&mdash;Oh, oh! That's the blank he
<PB N="62" REF="70">
wants to fill up, is it?&mdash;I am glad I &s;hall be able to vex him&mdash;don't be afraid of his wor&s;hip, my Lord&mdash;I have all my life been u&s;ed to counteract ju&s;tice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then lo&s;e not a moment, for I am all impatience to enjoy the fruits of thy indu&s;try;&mdash;and hem! hem!&mdash;the devil take this cough, I &s;ay. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JANUS</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>alone.</STAGE>
<P>Well, this is a good morning's walk&mdash;to &s;atisfy one's intere&s;t and one's revenge at the &s;ame time, by &s;e|curing the principal evidence on both &s;ides the que&s;tion&mdash;and I think we need not fear being cro&s;s-examined.&mdash;I am glad his lord&s;hip has employed me in this bu&s;ine&s;s, otherwi&s;e I mu&s;t have obeyed her lady&s;hip; but when one is engaged on both &s;ides, one can &s;atisfy one's con|&s;cience, and take that which is mo&s;t agreeable. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">Mi&s;s <HI>PENELOPE ZODIAC</HI>'s Dre&s;&s;ing-Room; &s;he &s;itting at a Table, with a Letter in her Hand.</HEAD>
<P>I think this is the time Colonel Quorum reque&s;ted an interview; and it would be exceedingly rude not to be punctual with military gentlemen.&mdash;Be&s;ides, with what a polite warmth he writes&mdash;<Q>&startq;I die with impatience to thank you for your conde&s;cen&s;ion, which I am now reading from your fair hand.&endq;</Q>&mdash;Yes, yes, I certainly have &s;truck him, notwith&s;tanding the reports about that creature Loui&s;a.&mdash;If he &s;hould pre&s;s me, I mu&s;t relent, however, with a proper cruelty.</P>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Servant</HI> to announce the <HI>Colonel.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shew him in&mdash;&s;hew him in.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>COLONEL QUORUM,</HI> (bowing very low.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Madam, forgive my eagerne&s;s to ex|pre&s;s
<PB N="63" REF="71">
my &s;en&s;e of your kindne&s;s.&mdash;I &s;hould have addre&s;s'd my&s;elf, in the fir&s;t place, to Lady Betty, as having the honour of a greater intimacy; but Mi&s;s Penelope Zodiac has a heart as amiable as her per&s;on, and will forgive the intru&s;ion of a &s;oldier and a magi&s;trate, who comes to her as a tender &s;uppliant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord, Colonel, you put me quite in a flutter.&mdash;I &s;hould be &s;orry to refu&s;e Colonel Quorum any proper reque&s;t&mdash;but&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be not alarm'd, dear Mi&s;s Penelope.&mdash;Col. Quorum, I am bold to &s;ay, wou'd not abu&s;e the kindne&s;s of any Lady; and you, Madam, will allow for the feelings of a man in love.&mdash;If I can but per&s;uade her to intere&s;t her&s;elf for me with Loui&s;a, it wou'd go a great way. <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I &s;ee how it is. <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>&mdash;I beg, Sir, you will be &s;eated <STAGE>(both &s;it):</STAGE>&mdash;and &s;o, Colonel, I think you &s;aid you was in love.&mdash;Girls, indeed, are fond of coquetting&mdash;but a &s;en&s;ible woman &s;corns to give unnece&s;|&s;ary pain.&mdash;I a&s;&s;ure you I feel for your &s;ituation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Madam, you, who are &s;o kind, wou'd pardon my warmth, if you were &s;en&s;ible of the charms of her whom I adore.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, Sir, I am afraid you do but flat|ter me.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Rather, Madam, &s;ay you flatter me&mdash;but, to be plain, tho' a friend to the &s;i&s;ter, you may, perhaps, be ignorant of the libertine principles of Lord Hectic.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Truly, Colonel, I am no &s;tranger to them.&mdash;Indeed I have often thought, though only a vi&s;itor, a kind of &s;atellite, as I may call my&s;elf, in the&s;e regions, that I'm not entirely &s;afe in the hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>O Madam, you wou'd really be alarm'd, if you knew the de&s;igns he is capable of forming.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>How, Colonel!&mdash;you frighten me to
<PB N="64" REF="72">
death.&mdash;I won't &s;tay another night within his atmo&s;phere.&mdash;Oh, Colonel, it is on the&s;e occa&s;ions a &s;ingle lady wants mo&s;t a protector.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>True, Madam;&mdash;and Col. Quorum&punc; when he is not bound to keep the peace, does not want the &s;pirit to protect any lady;&mdash;but how mortifying it wou'd be, if tho&s;e efforts were di&s;regarded, and his atten|tions were of no avail! <STAGE>(in a tender accent.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>And cannot you, who are a &s;oldier&punc; read any thing from the eyes&mdash;the manner that approves, though it &s;ays nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>How good you are!&mdash;would you but deign to unite your intere&s;t with mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, Colonel, pray &s;upport me&mdash;I'm in a &s;trange taking.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Deare&s;t Madam, will you then con&s;ent to my propo&s;al?&mdash;Will you e&s;pou&s;e my cau&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heavens!&mdash;how my heart beats.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(more earne&s;t)</STAGE> Say, deare&s;t Madam, that you will be the mi&s;tre&s;s of my fate on this oc|ca&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Colonel, I relent&mdash;I am yours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(ki&s;&s;ing her hand)</STAGE> I am tran&s;ported&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(looking tenderly)</STAGE> But will you be &s;o always, when you become my hu&s;band, Colonel?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(&s;tarting up)</STAGE> Madam!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Colonel, I &s;ee you are &s;urpri&s;ed at my kindne&s;s&mdash;perhaps &s;ome women would have been more cruel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Madam, I fear we mi&s;under&s;tand each other.&mdash;By Heaven I cannot but be &s;en&s;ible of the honour you have done me&mdash;but, in truth, my heart is en|gaged to one in who&s;e intere&s;t I hoped to have made you a partaker&mdash;the divine Loui&s;a.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(&s;tarting up)</STAGE> What! and have you been
<PB N="65" REF="73">
deceiving me into a pa&s;&s;ion all this time, and &s;educing me into an un&s;u&s;pected avowal of regard, merely to play upon me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Deare&s;t Madam&mdash;be pacified.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>And is it thus you impo&s;e upon young ladies?&mdash;Fie for &s;hame.&mdash;You a &s;oldier, and a ju&s;tice!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, Mi&s;s Penelope, by all that's mili|tary and legal, I am mo&s;t heartily &s;orry for the mi&s;take.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;take, Sir! don't call it mi&s;take&mdash;Did you not write to me?&mdash;Did you not talk of my fair hands?&mdash;Have you not, you audacious fellow?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(in a pa&s;&s;ion)</STAGE> Zounds and perdition!&mdash;but I am temperate.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I in&s;i&s;t upon your &s;eeing me no more.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>I obey.&mdash;Military gentlemen &s;eem born to di&s;tre&s;s the ladies&mdash;but, as a magi&s;trate, I ought not to be a di&s;turber of the peace. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, this is a &s;hock indeed to my fir&s;t pa&s;&s;ion, and requires all the philo&s;ophy I am mi&s;tre&s;s of.&mdash;But, thank Heaven, nobody knows it but my&s;elf.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE IV.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">A &s;mall room in <HI>LOUISA'S</HI> cottage&mdash;a table, with paper, ink, &amp;c.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOUISA</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>with a letter.</STAGE>
<P>When will relentle&s;s Fortune cea&s;e its per&s;ecutions&punc; this is indeed a cruel aggravation of my &s;orrows <STAGE>(look|ing at the letter)</STAGE> to be accu&s;ed by my Harriet of having &s;educed the affections of her Belcour, whom, &s;he tells me, &s;he has lo$t for ever:&mdash;<Q>&startq;to reproach me in terms the mo&s;t re&s;entful, and tear a bleeding bo&s;om with the &s;harpe&s;t poignard of unkindne&s;s&mdash;yet I forgive her&mdash;
<PB N="66" REF="74">
too well I know how &s;evere a trial it is to lo&s;e that object on whom our fir&s;t affections have been placed&endq;</Q>&mdash;before I go, I will unfold to her my fatal &s;tory, and convince her how impo&s;&s;ible it is that I, the child of woe, the victim of &s;en&s;ibility, could have been guilty of &s;uch ba&s;ene&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ANNA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Anna.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, the chai&s;e is ready&mdash;but, oh! my dear, my honoured lady&mdash;let me again entreat.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Anna, I mu&s;t leave you&mdash;I cannot however bear a formal parting&mdash;you know, and will remember my wi&s;hes&mdash;take my boy in your hand, and, together with this packet, wait upon Mr. Lovele&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Anna.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, my dear lady&mdash;but perhaps there will be no occa&s;ion&mdash;I met Mr. Lovele&s;s ju&s;t now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is it you mean?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Anna.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray don't be angry with me&mdash;but he &s;eemed &s;o pre&s;&s;ing, I told him where you lived, and he promis'd to call upon you directly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(more alarmed)</STAGE> Promis'd to call upon me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Anna.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope, Madam, you are not offended&mdash;but indeed he was &s;o kind to the child, and enquir'd &s;o ten|derly after you. <STAGE>(knocking at the door)</STAGE>&mdash;O Madam, there he is&mdash;and to be &s;ure he is the civille&s;t be&s;t gentleman&mdash;I am certain you'll be glad to &s;ee him. <STAGE>[runs out.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(greatly agitated)</STAGE> What now remains for me?&mdash;Fate thou ha&s;t done thy wor&s;t; the deepe&s;t woes, the pure&s;t intentions, could not avert thy rigour. I would have &s;aved my child from &s;hame&mdash;I would have &s;ought my father's humble roof, and then in &s;ome ob&s;cure cor|ner have implored his leave to linger out the little rem|nant of my days&mdash;O nature &s;upport me&mdash;he is coming.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="67" REF="75">
<HI>Enter</HI> JANUS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, your mo&s;t obedient&mdash;I beg you will not be &s;urpriz'd at my appearance&mdash;tho' I am a &s;tranger, I'm quite a gentleman, I a&s;&s;ure you, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, pray Sir&mdash;to what cau&s;e am I indebted for the honour of this vi&s;it?&mdash;I am indeed unacquainted with your per&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Perhaps &s;o&mdash;but I believe I'm as well known at the quarter-&s;e&s;&s;ions as mo&s;t people&mdash;I have the honour to be an attorney, and to manage the concerns of my Lord Hectic&mdash;I think you are acquainted with his Lord&s;hip&mdash;he is a mo&s;t amiable man, I a&s;&s;ure you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>It may be &s;o, Sir&mdash;but I hope you will not think me impertinent in &s;aying, I have particular bu&s;i|ne&s;s at pre&s;ent.&mdash;Should Lovele&s;s come&mdash;<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o have I&mdash;I like bu&s;ine&s;s of all things, and do a great deal for his Lord&s;hip: no offence, I hope.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, Sir, be kind enough not to trouble me about Lord Hectic, or any <HI>other</HI> per&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly not, Ma'am&mdash;never give trouble without &s;hewing cau&s;e.&mdash;Really now this is a pretty gen|teel hou&s;e you have got into&mdash;very neatly furni&s;h'd in|deed&mdash;I dare &s;ay you mu&s;t pay very hand&s;omely for it&mdash;belongs, I think, to Lord Hectic;&mdash;no offence, I hope&mdash;but his Lord&s;hip is rather a punctual man, and apt to enquire about rents&mdash;never &s;uffers a tenant to quit the premi&s;es till all is di&s;charged.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Sir, if this hou&s;e does belong to Lord Hectic&mdash;of which I was ignorant, or, on many accounts, I &s;hould not have entered its doors&mdash;I have left orders to di&s;charge faithfully all my debts&mdash;however there's what will &s;atisfy you <STAGE>(offers him money)</STAGE> in the mean time, I beg you will no longer bar my pa&s;&s;age. <STAGE>(going)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="68" REF="76">
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(interrupting her)</STAGE> Dear Madam, I hope y$ will not think of it&mdash;be&s;ides, I can't give a proper re|ceipt, I have no &s;tamps&mdash;My Lord loves to &s;ettle the&s;e matters him&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I in&s;i&s;t upon freedom in my own hou&s;e&mdash;I hope you will not think of &s;topping me&mdash;I beg, Sir, I may pa&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(&s;topping her)</STAGE> Yes, Madam&mdash;I remember a ca&s;e&mdash;2d of Charles the I&s;t.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>O Heavens! if Lovele&s;s &s;hou'd now enter! <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>&mdash;What, Sir, is your brea&s;t incapable of &s;ympa|thy? Have you no compa&s;&s;ion for the &s;orrows of an helple&s;s female?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, 2d of Charles the I&s;t.&mdash;as I &s;aid&mdash;there was a negro-woman that had got into a hou&s;e&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you then mean to in&s;ult me? O Provi|dence!&mdash;but I &s;ubmit to thy decrees&mdash;and is there no one to feel for my affliction?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Madam, to be &s;ure&mdash;wait upon Lord Hectic, and the whole will be &s;ettled immediately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Wait upon Lord Hectic, Sir!&mdash;there is no hou&s;e on earth I would not &s;ooner go to&mdash;no place &s;o terrible, except the pre&s;ent&mdash;Heavens! I &s;hall run di&s;|tracted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, Madam, don't he&s;itate.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>ANNA</HI> ha&s;tily.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Anna.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear lady, I'm &s;o glad&mdash;Mr. Lovele&s;s is coming acro&s;s the meadow, and will be here in a few minutes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(falling on her knees)</STAGE> O Sir, on my knees let me implore your pity&mdash;'tis not pecuniary relief I want&mdash;take twice the &s;um that I am indebted&mdash;'tis an unhappy woman, torn with ten thou&s;and agonizing pangs, that kneels for $our compa&s;&s;ion, and only begs permi&s;&s;ion to
<PB N="69" REF="77">
retire&mdash;I would not for the world be &s;een by Mr. Lovele&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not &s;een by Mr. Lovele&s;s&mdash;&s;ome former keeper, I &s;uppo&s;e; it will be as well to take advantage of this di&s;covery. <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>&mdash;Ri&s;e, Madam, I would not for the world you &s;hould be caught&mdash;you may depend upon my &s;ilence&mdash;there's no occa&s;ion to declare the whole truth, you know, unle&s;s one's &s;worn in court&mdash;&s;o, Ma|dam, as your chai&s;e is at the door, we can pop into it, and drive to my Lord's together; for <HI>we mu&s;t</HI> have your di&s;|charge from him&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(ri&s;ing)</STAGE> I &s;ee, Sir, you are inexorable.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Ma'am, very con&s;cientious in the di&s;|charge of my duty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>To go there is dreadful&mdash;to &s;tay here is ruin.&mdash;Lead on, Sir&mdash;I can brave any &s;hock but this.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(going out)</STAGE> Gad, this di&s;tre&s;s is very fortu|nate&mdash;I &s;hould never have carried my point without it.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(to Anna, who is following)</STAGE> Tarry a while, my Anna&mdash;and tell the &s;tranger, when he comes to hear how rudely I have been driven from this la&s;t and only &s;helter&mdash;tell him, that Loui&s;a's wrongs, her cea&s;ele&s;s angui&s;h, and her &s;horten'd life, will one day ri&s;e in dreadful evi|dence again&s;t the cruel author of them all. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<TRAILER>END OF THE FOURTH ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<PB N="70" REF="78">
<HEAD>ACT V.</HEAD>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">A Saloon in <HI>LORD HECTIC'S</HI> Hou&s;e.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>LOVELESS,</HI> much agitated.</STAGE>
<P>YES, the di&s;tinction is ju&s;t, and I feel its force&mdash;guilty as I have been, dare I revolt again&s;t any epithet of reproach which the father of my Julia here be&s;tows upon me?&mdash;Yes, I <HI>have outrag'd</HI> the peace of an innocent family, and call'd Heaven to witne&s;s the viola|tion of its own rites. Can I then oppo&s;e my&s;elf again&s;t the life of a parent, who&s;e wrongs already ri&s;e beyond re|dre&s;s? I &s;hudder at the thought.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> BELCOUR.</STAGE>
<P>Oh, my friend, excu&s;e the ha&s;te with which I &s;ent to you&mdash;indeed your pre&s;ence is mo&s;t welcome.</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Lovele&s;s, I in&s;tantly obey'd your &s;ummons&mdash;but &s;ay, explain to me the cau&s;e of this emotion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(giving a letter)</STAGE> Read that&mdash;and you will know.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Belcour reads.</STAGE>
<LETTER>
<OPENER><SALUTE>Sir,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>The offer of a pecuniary recompence I treat with the contempt it merits, becau&s;e I find how deeply I have been injured. While I look'd upon my child as a wanton, who yielded to the &s;olicitation, the di&s;ho|nourable
<PB N="71" REF="79">
&s;olicitation, of a pretended lover, I held her cau&s;e beneath the dignity of a &s;oldier's arm; an arm worn in the honourable &s;ervice of his country, never &s;ullied in the defence of infamy and &s;hame&mdash;but when I learn, for the fir&s;t time, &s;he has been betray'd by a pretended &s;olemnization of marriage, and that &s;he has fallen a victim to that fraud, and my unju&s;t di&s;plea&s;ure; every remembrance of my un|happy child now upbraids the tardine&s;s of my arm&mdash;old as I am&mdash;and &s;inking beneath the pre&s;&s;ure of my woes, I have <HI>flown</HI> to this &s;pot; and &s;hall only add, that I expect you an hour hence, at the out&s;kirts of the grove.</P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED>Frederic Hardy.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</LETTER>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(taking back the letter)</STAGE> Well&mdash;is he not right?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>The warmth of a parent is natural, and ought to be excu&s;ed. You, however, mu&s;t not be pro|vok'd at it&mdash;meeting him would be impo&s;&s;ible.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, &s;o I have thought&mdash;but then, my friend, can I &s;ubmit to epithets, under which no man ought to live?&mdash;Should he &s;tigmatize me as a coward, will the world make allowances for my &s;ituation, or be|lieve that he is the only man on earth I would not meet?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>And would you then &s;o far comply with the fal&s;e idea which that world calls honour, as to rai&s;e your arm again&s;t a man already too much injured?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;take me not&mdash;I have no &s;uch intention&mdash;I have been the aggre&s;&s;or; and 'tis proper, if &s;uch is the reparation he wi&s;hes, that I &s;hou'd abide its con&s;e|quence&mdash;yes, I will meet him&mdash;but without re&s;i&s;tance&mdash;I &s;hall offer my&s;elf a willing victim to his re&s;entment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Lovele&s;s, if &s;uch are your re&s;olu|tions, let me at lea&s;t go with you&mdash;perhaps it may be in my power to convince Captain Hardy, that, notwith|&s;tanding
<PB N="72" REF="80">
the &s;avage practice we &s;ee every day enforced, a duel never yet afforded a recompence for a wrong&mdash;life may be taken, but &s;atisfaction will not be obtained: and I &s;ubmit it to every thinking man, who has unfortunately been led into &s;uch a &s;ituation, whether, the moment re|venge was complete, peace of mind was not de&s;troyed? I mu&s;t in&s;i&s;t, therefore, on being permitted to attend you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Belcour, that painful ta&s;k let me excu&s;e you: in the&s;e ca&s;es an indifferent man is be&s;t; for, though it be the ta&s;k of a friend, it is the la&s;t office he &s;hould undertake. On this occa&s;ion I mean to a&s;k the kindne&s;s of Lord Hectic&mdash;his &s;en&s;ibility will not &s;uffer as an ac|quaintance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Unkind Lovele&s;s! And can you imagine I &s;hall &s;uffer le&s;s, becau&s;e I am not pre&s;ent?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray &s;pare me. <STAGE>(as going)</STAGE>&mdash;One thing, how|ever, I wi&s;h to mention&mdash;Should any thing happen, &s;hould this be the la&s;t time I embrace my friend, the fa|ther of my Julia will &s;till find I have not forgotten him. The bulk of my fortune, however, you will be the heir to&mdash;if therefore a wi&s;h for your Harriet &s;till hangs about your heart, let my la&s;t reque&s;t enforce your own appli|cation, for her to &s;hare it with you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am overpower'd by your goodne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>One thing more&mdash;I have taken the liberty of leaving a &s;mall beque&s;t to the lady in who&s;e cau&s;e we have intere&s;ted our&s;elves: and, according to my promi&s;e, have &s;ecured the independency of her &s;on. Should &s;he wonder why a &s;tranger has been thus attentive to her concerns, inform her of my &s;tory, and tell her it was the peace-offering of a man who had once injured the pure&s;t of female excellence. <STAGE>[Exit ha&s;tily.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="73" REF="81">
<SPEAKER>BELCOUR.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(&s;olus)</STAGE>
<P>Generous Lovele&s;s! Be it mine, in return for thy friend&s;hip, to prevent any advantage I might receive from thy misfortune.&mdash;Poor Harriet! Lovele&s;s would u&s;e thee tenderly&mdash;but I have treated thee with unkind|ne&s;s. She now &s;u&s;pects me of an unworthy attachment to her once-loved friend Loui&s;a, and bitterly upbraids us both:&mdash;let me then ha&s;te to undeceive her; and, regardle&s;s of worldly con&s;iderations, lay my erring heart at her feet, and rely upon the tenderne&s;s of her's to pardon and ac|cept it. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">A cabinet in <HI>LORD HECTIC'S</HI> hou&s;e, hung round with pic|tures of ladies. One frame empty. He &s;urveying them with a pocket-gla&s;s, and du&s;ting them with his pocket-hand|kerchief.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Lord</HI> HECTIC.</SPEAKER>
<P>A man of fa&s;hion &s;hould patronize the arts; and there|fore, whenever I &s;ucceed with a lady, I always have her picture drawn; by which means I encourage painting, and perpetuate my own atchievements. <STAGE>(Looking at the empty frame)</STAGE> I mu&s;t have that vacancy though filled up: I ordered the frame, I think, when I fir&s;t conceived a pa&s;&s;ion for Loui&s;a;&mdash;hem!&mdash;$t will really fully, if I am not happy in a &s;hort time.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SWAGGER.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>What the devil can you mean by poring over a trumpery frame, that you intend to make into a
<PB N="74" REF="82">
picture, though upon my &s;houl the original will never come after the copy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>What the devil art thou talking about? Why thou art drunk&mdash;ab&s;olutely drunk.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Faith! and I am no &s;uch thing, honey!&mdash;I am as &s;o&mdash;ber as any gentleman ought to be, that is a &s;oldier, d'ye &s;ee.&mdash;So I tell you now, in &s;ober &s;adne&s;s, you may give up all thoughts of Madam Loui&s;a, for &s;he has fixed her &s;weet affections upon another per&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hem! hem! <STAGE>(coughing)</STAGE>&mdash;You really have choaked me:&mdash;fix'd her affections upon another!&mdash;what?&mdash;Whom do you mean?&mdash;how?&mdash;when?&mdash;where?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where!&mdash;why about two yards and a half from you. If you look &s;traight to me, you can't mi&s;s &s;eeing him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Captain Swagger! thou ha&s;t &s;ure|ly forgotten whom thou art &s;peaking of&mdash;and what thou art &s;aying.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, to be &s;ure! and I am to blame if &s;he has fixed her affections, as I &s;aid, upon a &s;ober gentleman|like per&s;on called Captain Swagger!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon thee&mdash;thou animal!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, by St. Patrick! for when I went there, ju&s;t to &s;peak a few words in your favour&mdash;Oh, &s;ays &s;he, Captain (with a &s;mile that quite bother'd me) how can you wa&s;te your time thus, when perhaps I may have di&s;po&s;ed of my heart to another?&mdash;<HI>Another!</HI>&mdash;Upon my &s;houl, and I take the&s;e things as quick as any man in all England.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Drunk&mdash;ab&s;olutely drunk.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> JANUS, <HI>and whi&s;pers</HI> LORD HECTIC.</STAGE>
<P>Loui&s;a coming to wait upon me!&mdash;hem! hem!</P>
<SP>
<PB N="75" REF="83">
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, only a little timorous, as &s;he is afraid of &s;ome former keeper, who has di&s;covered her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>You overcome me with gratitude, my dear friend;&mdash;twi&s;t your&s;elf out immediately, and drive that cou&s;in of mine before you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Janus.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, Captain, as you &s;eem very clear|headed, &s;uppo&s;e you retire to &s;tudy a little in my Lord's library. <STAGE>(&s;hoving him)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, I will go and &s;tudy&mdash;but I am the mo&s;t complai&s;ant crater in the world, to leave a room when a woman is in love with me. <STAGE>(Janus pu&s;hes him out)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hem! hem!&mdash;Upon my word this un|expected vi&s;it has a little deranged my nerves.&mdash;Where the devil is my tincture of &s;age, to give me confidence?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LOUISA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord, you will doubtle&s;s be &s;urprized at &s;o extraordinary a vi&s;it, from one who&s;e misfortunes alone are all &s;he has to plead&mdash;misfortunes which your Lord|&s;hip has (I hope unintentionally) very con&s;iderably in|crea&s;ed. Depre&s;&s;ed with curele&s;s griefs, and nearly yield|ing to a &s;ad de&s;pondency, I had found one kind a&s;ylum, I had &s;ecured one tender friend:&mdash;friend&s;hip and privacy, the only con&s;olations I could feel, your Lord&s;hip's impor|tunities have deprived me of&mdash;but I cannot, will not, &s;up|po&s;e your heart has con&s;ented to &s;uch injurious conduct&mdash;and therefore have determined to make this per&s;onal appeal to your compa&s;&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Really, upon my word, you did very right.&mdash;She begins in heroics, I &s;ee&mdash;a certain &s;ign &s;he'll come down. <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>&mdash;Pray, Madam, be &s;eated.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="76" REF="84">
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg, my Lord, we may wave attentions&mdash;I have already too much rea&s;on to complain of yours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Madam, I hope not&mdash;I &s;hou'd be the mo&s;t mortified creature breathing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>A per&s;on who informs me he acts for your lord&s;hip, has &s;ubjected me to great inconvenience; it is in your power to oblige me mo&s;t e&s;&s;entially&mdash;There is a gentleman&mdash;I hope I may &s;peak with confidence&mdash;nobody can break in upon your lord&s;hip?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, not a &s;oul&mdash;however I'll take the pre|caution of locking the door.&mdash;Yes, I &s;ee the frame will &s;oon be filled up. <STAGE>(returns from the door)</STAGE>&mdash;You may de|pend upon it, Madam, we are &s;afe. I am exceedingly nice about a lady's reputation, and never mention a thing afterwards.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let me then hope you will put a &s;top to the inju&s;tice which your lawyer has been guilty of in your name.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>O dear, madam, never mind&mdash;you know what an attorney is, and won't be &s;urprized at any thing he does.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed I imagined his conduct wou'd never meet with your concurrence; and &s;ome rea&s;ons, peculiar to my fortune and &s;ituation, making my immediate retreat nece&s;&s;ary, I was induced to take this &s;tep&mdash;perhaps too forward&mdash;that I might not &s;uffer the delays of imperti|nence, or the in&s;ults of mean power.&mdash;From your lord|&s;hip, notwith&s;tanding former mi&s;takes, I tru&s;ted a help|le&s;s female would find &s;ecurity and redre&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Without doubt, Madam&mdash;I a&s;&s;ure you you are quite &s;afe&mdash;pray do not ri&s;e&mdash;nothing can be more &s;nug. <STAGE>(knock)</STAGE>&mdash;<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> What the devil is that? <STAGE>(&s;tart|ing up.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(ri&s;ing)</STAGE> I beg, my Lord, you will u&s;e no ce|remony&mdash;I would not be &s;een for the world&mdash;I can retire
<PB N="77" REF="85">
the other way.&mdash;Here is the full amount of my debt.</P>
<STAGE>(going.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, Madam&mdash;I reque&s;t, I entreat <STAGE>(knock|ing)</STAGE>&mdash;Zounds! was ever nobleman &s;o interrupted?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(without)</STAGE> My Lord, I a&s;k your pardon&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>O Heavens Lovele&s;s's voice <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't be alarmed&mdash;it is only a gentle|man, whom you don't know&mdash;a vi&s;itor of mine&mdash;a queer formal &s;ort of fellow&mdash;Do me the favour only to &s;tep into that room, I'll turn him out again in an in&s;tant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(without)</STAGE> Pray, my Lord, let me &s;peak to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(calling to him)</STAGE> In a minute, Lovele&s;s&mdash;in a minute.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>What &s;hall I do?&mdash;Should he di&s;cover me in this &s;ituation, how dreadful will it be! <STAGE>(going towards the apartment.)</STAGE> Let me entreat you not to mention my name, or even hint that a lady is here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly not, Ma'am&mdash;I'm the mo&s;t careful man about a lady's reputation. <STAGE>(&s;hews her into the other room)</STAGE>&mdash;Damn this fellow's interruption; what can he want, an impertinent ra&s;cal? <STAGE>(opens the door.)</STAGE>&mdash;My dear friend, I am very glad to &s;ee you&mdash;but how the devil could you interrupt a man at &s;uch a cri&s;is?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg your pardon, my Lord, if I have in|truded&mdash;but the ca&s;e would not admit of delay&mdash;I mu&s;t reque&s;t your attention for a moment to a very di&s;agree|able bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am $orry for it&mdash;but I can attend to nothing now, but very plea&s;ant bu&s;ine&s;s.&mdash;Betwixt our|&s;elves, there is a lady in the other room&mdash;but &s;he de&s;ired me not to &s;peak of it&mdash;You under&s;tand me&mdash;when a lady's in the ca&s;e&mdash;hem! hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>I acknowledge the privilege&mdash;but in one
<PB N="78" REF="86">
word then, I am unfortunately involved in an affair of honour, and mu&s;t reque&s;t your a&s;&s;i&s;tance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds! how can I think of an affair of honour, when I have got a fine woman waiting for me&mdash;or what wou'd &s;he think of me, if I did?&mdash;why, I tell you its the hand&s;ome widow that I was mentioning, that you and Belcour were moralizing about&mdash;had not you unfortunately broke in upon me&mdash;the day had been mine already.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Really!&mdash;Loui&s;a a wanton!&mdash;then, indeed, I've been deceived&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>That may be&mdash;but I am never deceiv'd about the women. When I pur&s;ue, I always &s;ucceed.&mdash;Look at the&s;e pictures, they are my trophies&mdash;that frame will &s;oon be filled up&mdash;Loui&s;a's ready to &s;it; pop her in in a week:&mdash;but I don't &s;peak out of vanity.&mdash;So now, my dear friend, damn your duel, and turn your&s;elf out as quick as you can.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, my Lord, I will wait your lei&s;ure.&mdash;Succe&s;s is the parent of levity, and therefore I excu&s;e yours.&mdash;Unthinking Loui&s;a! thus to &s;acrifice thy&s;elf.&mdash;Had the angel whom I deceiv'd but re&s;embled thee, how &s;hort would have been my regret! <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(going to the door of the inner room)</STAGE> Well, all is &s;afe, my dame of Ephe&s;us&mdash;that damn'd fellow is gone. <STAGE>(Loui&s;a comes out)</STAGE> Come, don't be frighten'd, my angel&mdash;Lord Hectic is protection it&s;elf&mdash;hem! hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank Heaven, it is pa&s;t&mdash;and now, &s;ince I can depart with &s;ecurity, let me not again run the ri&s;k of &s;ubjecting my&s;elf and your lord&s;hip to the impertinence of &s;u&s;picion.&mdash;I wi&s;h you a good day. <STAGE>(going)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, Ma'am&mdash;I beg Ma'am, you will compo&s;e your&s;elf;&mdash;I could not think of letting you go &s;o&mdash;&s;o fright'ned and flurried as you mu&s;t have been!&mdash;tha$
<PB N="79" REF="87">
cur&s;ed fellow, who has no more nerves than a porter&mdash;pray &s;it down and compo&s;e your&s;elf, my love.</P>
<STAGE>(Offering to take her hand.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope, my Lord, you will give no rea&s;on to alter the favourable opinion I had begun to form of your humanity; or to repent the re&s;olution, which led me, in a moment of di&s;tre&s;s, to fly to your Lord&s;hip for protection.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, come, my dear Madam, you excel in heroics, and I love them at proper times; but ladies don't vi&s;it gentlemen for nothing.&mdash;I am a man of fa&s;hion and plea&s;ure!&mdash;hem! hem!&mdash;and I am ambitious to &s;ee you at the head of both:&mdash;&s;o come, throw a&s;ide this&mdash;this unnece&s;&s;ary re&s;erve. <STAGE>(Seizing her hand.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Free my hand, my Lord, this in&s;tant&mdash;or, by all that's &s;acred, I'll alarm the family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh dear! my family are alarmed at no|thing;&mdash;come, Ma'am, ta&s;te and happine&s;s are in your reach&mdash;a neat hou&s;e in London&mdash;four ponies for Hyde|park&mdash;con&s;ent, my angel&mdash;nay, you mu&s;t&mdash;you &s;hall&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>[Attempts to be rude, &s;he &s;creams, and <HI>Lovele&s;s</HI> ru&s;hes in; on which &s;he faints, and falls.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why what the devil brings you back again, Lovele&s;s? don't you &s;ee&punc; the lady faints at the &s;ight of you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(goes up to her)</STAGE> Gracious Powers! what miracle is this? can it be po&s;&s;ible?&mdash;can it be my Julia whom I &s;ee <STAGE>(rai&s;es her)</STAGE> in &s;uch a &s;ituation?&mdash;Speak! breathe! look! and relieve my agonizing doubts!&mdash;My Lord, my Lord, what excu&s;e can you make?&mdash;Revive, my adored Julia, and explain this my&s;tery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Egad, I have got into the wrong box; and I may as well get out of it as &s;oon as I can. <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>&mdash;Well, Mr. Lovele&s;s, if this is really your Julia, as you call her&mdash;I never tre&s;pa&s;s upon any gentleman's property,
<PB N="80" REF="88">
and therefore&mdash;hem!&mdash;I have the honour to wi&s;h you a good morning. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(&s;triving to rai&s;e her)</STAGE> And yet, to be found with a man of Lord Hectic's character!&mdash;My love! my wife! my long-lo&s;t Julia!&mdash;a&s;&s;ure your&s;elf you are in the hands of a man who would die to protect you&mdash;in the arms of your Lovele&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(&s;tarting)</STAGE> Lovele&s;s! Oh! <STAGE>(breaking from him)</STAGE> too well I recollect that name! the fatal, fatal cau&s;e of all my &s;ufferings!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let me thank Heaven that thou art &s;till alive!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I am alive&mdash;inhuman Lovele&s;s! alive to every wretchedne&s;s thy cruelty has heap'd upon me!&mdash;betray'd by thee, in youth's unguarded morn&mdash;I have liv'd the &s;corn of my &s;ex, and the &s;port of your's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have indeed been guilty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>My fir&s;t, my tendere&s;t love being ba&s;ely &s;acri|ficed to &s;ordid intere&s;t and mean ambition, I have been forced, with the keen pangs of wounded &s;en&s;ibility, to bear the weight of unde&s;erv'd reproach.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! &s;pare me, Julia&mdash;look on me as I am, an alter'd man&mdash;peace has been a &s;tranger to my bo&s;om, and remor&s;e and &s;orrow my con&s;tant companions, &s;ince we parted.&mdash;My heart is open but to the charms of virtue, and trembles only at the uncertainty of yours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>My child, thy much-wrong'd child, too cruel man! who now mu&s;t blu&s;h to own his birth, but for thy treachery would have &s;mil'd upon our mutual happine&s;s, and rais'd his infant voice to ble&s;s his father.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Madam, I feel, &s;everely feel the ju&s;tice of your complaints! yet I could urge &s;ome heart-felt $ighs, I could bring witne&s;&s;es of &s;ome repentant tears; tears which hourly trickled down my cheek, when I $hought the injured excellence, who&s;e memory made
<PB N="81" REF="89">
them flow, had long been lo&s;t to every earthly recom|pence.&mdash;I lov'd my boy, before I knew he was &s;o. I felt for his mother's wrongs, when I could little &s;uppo&s;e my&s;elf the &s;ad aggre&s;&s;or.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lovele&s;s, 'tis now too late to parley&mdash;you may awaken remembrance; you can never re&s;tore my peace.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am di&s;tracted with a thou&s;and thoughts&mdash;I de&s;troy'd thy innocence; yet dread to find it wanting&mdash;tell me then, in pity tell me, how it comes, that, after having evaded all my fond enquiries, I now find you in Lord Hectic's own apartments, and &s;tudiou&s;ly concealed at my approach?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir; u&s;urp the right which my credulity has given you, to upbraid me with misfortunes which, even at this late period, you have been the cau&s;e of.&mdash;But for Lovele&s;s, Lord Hectic had been unknown.&mdash;How|ever, con&s;cious of no ill, I di&s;claim ju&s;tification&mdash;and Mr. Lovele&s;s is, perhaps, the only man on earth to whom I am not &s;olicitous of appearing innocent; becau&s;e, him&s;elf having lo&s;t all that was valuable in my eyes, his approbation now can give me no concern.&mdash;I beg, Sir, that I may be permitted to depart. <STAGE>(going.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stay, I conjure you, &s;tay:&mdash;wrong'd as you have been by my crimes, and now, perhaps, wrong'd by my &s;u&s;picions, deign to forgive a man, who&s;e &s;trong affection has been his guilt:&mdash;by every tie of na|ture I entreat you, hear me; by our &s;on's welfare, by your hopes of happine&s;s hereafter, inform me why you have eluded all my anxious &s;earches, and found me only in the&s;e hated rooms?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>There was a time when I &s;hould not have been &s;u&s;pected on &s;uch grounds:&mdash;from the tenor of my conduct, even from my enemies, you will learn the
<PB N="82" REF="90">
inju&s;tice you are now guilty of.&mdash;But enough of words have pa&s;s'd between us.&mdash;In the retirement which I &s;hall &s;eek, and which I hope you will not attempt to invade, no reproaches of mine &s;hall wound your ear again. Oh, Lovele&s;s!&mdash;protect your &s;on&mdash;protect my only child&mdash;rear him in the paths of honour&mdash;teach him to avoid his father's errors&mdash;to lament his mother's fate!&mdash;So &s;hall my ebbing life know &s;omething of content; and my boy's ri&s;ing virtues &s;hade his parent's faults, when you can wound, and I can weep no more. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I will obey thy injunctions, and not break in upon thy grief.&mdash;Every pro&s;pect of a reconcilia|tion is now at an end&mdash;what then remains for me?&mdash;a father's rage&mdash;a father's vengeful &s;word. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">Another Apartment in <HI>LORD HECTIC'S</HI> Hou&s;e, with folding|doors in the back Scene.</HEAD>
<STAGE>LADY BETTY WORMWOOD <HI>and</HI> MISS PENELOPE ZODIAC, <HI>meeting in a great hurry.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fine doings here, indeed, Lady Betty!&mdash;&s;o that abominable Loui&s;a has got into the hou&s;e, at la&s;t!&mdash;Mercy on us!&mdash;What will become of me, as an un|married lady?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>True, Mi&s;s Penelope, you are in the right to be apprehen&s;ive in time;&mdash;I had ju&s;t heard of it from my maid.&mdash;If it was not proper that &s;ome people &s;hould think of title and fortune in a great family, I &s;hould actually give my brother up.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Paugh! The very hou&s;e is tainted with the creature.&mdash;But I have lock'd up my room, le&s;t &s;he
<PB N="83" REF="91">
&s;hould run away with &s;ome of my poetry.&mdash;Tho&s;e &s;ort of animals are glad to lay their hands upon any thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>As to your poetry, I believe you need not have been afraid; for &s;uch wretches only &s;teal things of value&mdash;but, at all events, the hu&s;&s;ey mu&s;t be di&s;po&s;ed of;&mdash;I &s;hall con&s;ult my attorney immediately&mdash;in the mean time, do me the favour to look thro' the key-hole of my Lord's library, and ob&s;erve what's going for|ward.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>I look thro' the key-hole!&mdash;Heaven knows what I may be witne&s;s to!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, my dear friend, throw a&s;ide the&s;e &s;cruples&mdash;nobody will &s;u&s;pect you, as you are a learned lady, you know, and not &s;uppo&s;ed to think about &s;uch things. But my brother wou'd never forgive me, tho' I do it entirely out of kindne&s;s to him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you really thought there wou'd be no harm in it, why I wou'd give a peep&mdash;merely tho' to oblige you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are too good.&mdash;How glad &s;he is to li&s;ten!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray take care that nobody comes.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> COLONEL QUORUM, <HI>ha&s;tily.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am &s;orry, Lady Betty, to be trou|ble&s;ome&mdash;but I have been informed, that a lawyer, on your account, has given great unea&s;ine&s;s to a lady for whom I have a mo&s;t profound regard. <STAGE>(&s;eeing Mi&s;s Penelope)</STAGE>&mdash;Mi&s;s Penelope, I a&s;k ten thou&s;and par|dons, I did not intend to mention my attachments any more in your company, but&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg, Colonel, you will not addre&s;s your improper di&s;cour&s;e to me; as I'm an unmarried woman, and cannot po&s;&s;ibly hear it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, if my lawyer has been guilty of any
<PB N="84" REF="92">
&s;everity again&s;t the per&s;on in que&s;tion, he did not per|haps know that Colonel Quorum was not very inqui|&s;itive about the <HI>character</HI> of the ladies for whom he profe&s;s'd a regard.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>The devil, Madam!&mdash;I a&s;k pardon for &s;wearing; but, zounds! her character has been mi&s;re|pre&s;ented&mdash;and your Lady&s;hip's u&s;age has driven her from the friends that value her, to &s;eek &s;helter, perhaps, in &s;olitude.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes:&mdash;at lea&s;t, if &s;he's not alone, I dare &s;ay &s;he has not above one per&s;on with her.&mdash;Ha! Lady Betty!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>One per&s;on!&mdash;who knows, but &s;he is now wandering thro' woods and wilds, friendle&s;s and unattended, and her tender frame expo&s;ed to every hard&s;hip?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>I won't &s;ay what her tender frame may be expo&s;ed to; but I am &s;ure, if &s;he is wandering thro' woods and wilds, &s;he has met with them in my Lord's library.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my honour, I can't comprehend what your Lady&s;hip means; but &s;ure, after the impor|tunities &s;he had already with&s;tood from your brother&mdash;&s;he de&s;erved every re&s;pect.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>But are you &s;o certain &s;he has with&s;tood tho&s;e importunities?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Confu&s;ion, Madam!&mdash;permit me to in|form you, that &s;he has with&s;tood the mo&s;t honourable temptations; I only wi&s;h that &s;he might appear, to con|found all the ill-natur'd &s;urmi&s;es of her enemies.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Colonel, if you are &s;o de&s;irous of her appearing, I believe you have nothing in the world to do, but to open that door.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds!&mdash;'tis impo&s;&s;ible!&mdash;and if I thought &s;o, I'd have the Po&s;&s;e Comitatus, and bring her
<PB N="85" REF="93">
to light immediately&mdash;I have already di&s;patch'd my clerk, with a &s;earch-warrant and two field-pieces, to Sir Gregory Glovetop's; and by Heavens I'll leave no corner un&s;earch'd!&mdash;nay, I'll break the door open my|&s;elf;&mdash;am I not a ju&s;tice of peace? and don't I know the law upon the&s;e matters?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope he will do it.&mdash;How I &s;hall en|joy the creature's confu&s;ion!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay, in the King's name, open the door, that ju&s;tice may enter, and guilt be put to flight.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(throwing open the Gla&s;s Doors, and coming out half a&s;leep.)</STAGE> The devil burn me, but what is all this bother here?&mdash;Can't a gentleman &s;tudy, without being interrupted?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>There, Madam, I told you there was nothing pure in that apartment; and the Captain is a proof of it!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pure, Colonel! I never thought there was&mdash;but I &s;hall be look'd on as a fallen &s;tar my&s;elf, if I &s;tay any longer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>Some people will not believe their own eyes, nor other people their own ears&mdash;but, thank Hea|ven! my &s;en&s;es are perfect; and I &s;hall take my leave of people who have lo&s;t theirs. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, to be &s;ure&mdash;the ignorance of &s;ome folks is a&s;toni&s;hing. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(&s;peaking after them)</STAGE> Yes, ladies, and the malice of others.&mdash;But, by Heaven, if Lord Hectic only dares to &s;ay that he has <HI>&s;een</HI> an apartment belonging to Loui&s;a; or if you, Sir,&mdash;but I know the &s;tate of your feelings already, and how little they re&s;emble tho&s;e of your countrymen.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my &s;houl, if any body knows any
<PB N="86" REF="94">
thing of my feeling, its more than I do&mdash;and by my faith they may keep their knowledge to them&s;elves.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shew me the way to his Lord&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hew you the way!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Blood and thunder!&mdash;do you di&s;|pute?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Swagger.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, by no means&mdash;I'd &s;ooner &s;hew you to the devil.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[G$es through the folding-doors, <HI>Colonel</HI> following.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE IV.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">The Grove.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> CAPTAIN HARDY <HI>and</HI> LOVELESS, <HI>meeting.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Hardy.</SPEAKER>
<P>At length then we are met&mdash;few words are be&s;t, when language wou'd but ill de&s;cribe the weight of guilt, or paint the feelings of an injur'd parent. Come, Sir, draw and defend your&s;elf&mdash;ju&s;tice upbraids my &s;low revenge, and my poor child's departed &s;pirit calls on her father to vindicate her memory.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold, Captain Hardy! hold!&mdash;nor force me to rai&s;e my arm again&s;t a man for whom my heart already bleeds.&mdash;Your daughter lives.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Hardy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Paltry artifice!&mdash;Her death, alas! is not le&s;s certain to me than her di&s;honour&mdash;therefore drop this un|nece&s;&s;ary parley, and what you cannot ju&s;tify, dare at lea&s;t defend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>For Heaven's &s;ake, Sir, urge me no farther&mdash;at lea&s;t &s;atisfy your&s;elf of the reality of your daughter's exi&s;tence. On my honour &s;he lives&mdash;lives to con&s;ole your afflictions; would I could add, to join her entreaties to mine, to bury your re&s;entment!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Hardy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Impo&s;&s;ible&mdash;'tis nothing but a mean &s;ubter|fuge.&mdash;Draw, I in&s;i&s;t upon it, this moment&mdash;for, &s;unk and
<PB N="87" REF="95">
de&s;picable as thou art, not even the contempt thou me|rite&s;t &s;hall &s;ave thee. <STAGE>(they fight.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LOUISA, HARRIOT, BELCOUR, <HI>and the</HI> CHILD.</STAGE>
<STAGE>(She throws her&s;elf on her knees between them.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold, hold, your vengeful arms&mdash;&s;ee at your feet the unhappy cau&s;e of all your animo&s;ity.&mdash;O, my father&mdash;let me not lo&s;e that title in the very moment I re|cover it&mdash;make not an orphan of my infant child.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Hardy.</SPEAKER>
<P>My daughter alive!&mdash;imploring tho&s;e who mo&s;t have wrong'd her!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, my honour'd &s;ire&mdash;your long-lo&s;t daugh|ter &s;ues for your compa&s;&s;ion. Oh, my father&mdash;will you forgive the errors of my youth&mdash;pardon the &s;orrows I have brought upon you&mdash;and, in mercy to your daughter, &s;heath your &s;word?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Hardy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ri&s;e, my child.&mdash;You are not the offender&mdash;but you know not what you a&s;k&mdash;your &s;ufferings now call louder for redre&s;s. <STAGE>(offering again to fight, prevented by <HI>BELCOUR)</HI></STAGE> Well, Sir, we &s;hall yet meet&mdash;<STAGE>(putting up his &s;word)</STAGE> a father's vengeance cannot be eluded.&mdash;My child's misfortunes do not want forgivene&s;s&mdash;but her un|merited di&s;grace <HI>&s;hall be atoned.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belcour.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray let me interpo&s;e&mdash;as friend to all, as friend to nature and humanity.&mdash;<Q>&startq;My Harriet too, the companion of your daughter's lonely hours, &s;hall join her &s;olicitations to mine&mdash;we have both been faithful witne&s;&s;es of Lovele&s;s's contrition and his pangs, when they mu&s;t have been &s;incere&endq;</Q>&mdash;had he fallen by your arm, the la&s;t di&s;tribution of his effects would have done credit to his honour, to his affection, to his repentance. We have painted them all to your daughter, and nature pleads &s;trongly on his &s;ide&mdash;let your con&s;ent then autho|rize her forgivene&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="88" REF="96">
<SPEAKER>Hardy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your forgivene&s;s!&mdash;and is it &s;o, my child?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>O frown not on me, Sir&mdash;doom'd to long an|gui&s;h and uncea&s;ing tears, merited perhaps by my own unguardedne&s;s, never again &s;hall your Julia indulge her feelings, but when your approbation fir&s;t &s;anctifies her choice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Hardy.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(taking her hand)</STAGE> Spoke like the daughter my heart pants again to be allied with&mdash;look then with re|&s;entment on a man who left thee to &s;orrow and to &s;hame&mdash;Come, my poor &s;uffering child, and &s;hew that in&s;olent, who dar'd reject thee in his proude&s;t hour, that thou can'&s;t ri&s;e above the day of thy humiliation. <STAGE>(offers to lead her out)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(in great agitation)</STAGE> Let my dear boy then, our pledge of former tenderne&s;s, remain with me; and make me &s;ome amends for the lo&s;s of his unrelenting grand&s;ire, and too cruel mother.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(looking at her father, then at <HI>Lovele&s;s)</HI></STAGE> O, Sir, forgive me, if nature claims one tear, that yet rends my heart!&mdash;and tell me, oh, my father&mdash;tell me how&mdash;how a parent ought to act&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harriet.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(advancing with the child)</STAGE> Look, Sir, on this blamele&s;s infant, who&s;e childhood has been mark'd with calamity,&mdash;who&s;e growing years can open only to his father's angui&s;h, and his mother's grief&mdash;think that your forgivene&s;s can obliterate them all&mdash;and then deny it to him, if you can.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Hardy.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am conquer'd&mdash;I am not proof again&s;t that innocent <STAGE>(cla&s;ping the child)</STAGE>&mdash;come, my poor mourner, to my aged arms, while yet I've life to &s;uccour you.&mdash;Oh! Lovele&s;s, forgive my ha&s;ty rage, your father now reque&s;ts it.&mdash;Approach, my child <STAGE>(to his daughter)</STAGE>&mdash;lend me your hand&mdash;thus I be&s;tow it; and thus with nature'$ tendere&s;t
<PB N="89" REF="97">
tie I bind it fa&s;t <STAGE>(placing the child between them)</STAGE>&mdash;ble&s;s the &s;weet in&s;trument of my forgivene&s;s, and cheri&s;h him as the &s;ource of your unfading love.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(embracing her)</STAGE> My Julia&mdash;my recover'd wife!&mdash;tears choak my utterance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lovele&s;s, to find thee thus&mdash;a convert to that charming tenderne&s;s, which, founded in honour alone, brings every permanent and &s;oft delight&mdash;to &s;ee my honour'd father &s;miling on his new-born joys&mdash;to cla&s;p my much-loy'd friend <STAGE>(to Harriet)</STAGE> and know her happy as her heart can de&s;ire, I will freely and gratefully ac|knowledge fate has not left me now one wi&s;h to form.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> COLONEL QUORUM.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Separate the parties immediately, I &s;ay, before they do any mi&s;chief.&mdash;While I am a magi&s;trate no duel &s;hall be tolerated.&mdash;Loui&s;a here!&mdash;I hope, Madam, you were not going to engage.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Colonel, and for life, I flatter my&s;elf&mdash;Loui&s;a is my Julia&mdash;is my wife&punc;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your wife!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do not wonder at your a&s;toni&s;hment; but you &s;oon &s;hall be appriz'd of every thing&mdash;you, Sir, are entitled to our confidence as well as friend&s;hip, for I know no one to whom this lady has been more oblig'd.&mdash;Your good opinion, I am inform'd, remained unaltered by her di&s;tre&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col. Quorum.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! I am afraid there was a little of &s;elf|love in that, after all.&mdash;But if you, Madam, can forget my pa&s;&s;ion, I will endeavour to forget it too.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LORD HECTIC.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Mr. Lovele&s;s, I &s;ee you are alive&mdash;
<PB N="90" REF="98">
and therefore I hope I am not too late for a &s;econd&mdash;The ladies here!&mdash;Oh&mdash;hem!&mdash;then Mars mu&s;t yield to Ve|nus.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LADY BETTY <HI>and</HI> MISS PENELOPE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Betty.</SPEAKER>
<P>My brother's voice!&mdash;then I am &s;ure the odious creature is not far off, and I dare &s;ay encircled with the men too.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Penelope.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, always wand'ring into another per&s;on's &s;phere.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Hardy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray who are the&s;e <HI>good-natured</HI> ladies, that are pleas'd to make &s;uch <HI>kind</HI> ob&s;ervations on my daughter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord Hectic.</SPEAKER>
<P>One of the&s;e ladies I have the honour to call &s;i&s;ter, and the other is a virgin aunt of this gen|tleman&mdash;but I really can't an&s;wer for either of their <HI>good|nature.</HI> However, Madam, as you are now in the po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of my friend Lovele&s;s&mdash;who I told you was a good &s;ort of man, only a little formal, I will give up my preten&s;ions, and fairly confe&s;s you are in better hands.&mdash;Ah! that frame mu&s;t remain vacant, I &s;ee. <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord, I thank you, and if you will per|mit me to offer you and the&s;e ladies one word of advice, it would be, that, while you de&s;i&s;ted from attempting to give cau&s;e for &s;candal, they &s;hould relinqui&s;h exerci&s;ing it without any cau&s;e at all.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SIR GREGORY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o, child, you have broke through all etiquette, and actually been forward enough to &s;tep out of my hou&s;e with a gentleman, perhaps of no precedence at all, and without a pedigree!&mdash;I &s;hould have been exceed|ingly angry, but I never am vex'd before good company.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lovele&s;s.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Gregory, Mr. Belcour is my friend, and his rank and fortune will entitle him, I believe, in your
<PB N="91" REF="99">
opinion, to pardon at court&mdash;and now let me introduce you to a lady, formerly an acquaintance of your's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Gregory.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, Loui&s;a!&mdash;very true&mdash;one of the hou&s;$|hold, I prote&s;t&mdash;ah I &s;aid, if &s;he had a proper idea of con&s;e|quence, and got quit of &s;orrow and affection, and all that, &s;he would do very well yet&mdash;and my little fellow here &s;hall be a page after all&mdash;and I'll keep my promi&s;e, and teach him the true court-&s;tep my&s;elf&mdash;ha! ha!&mdash;Soft and maje&s;tic, with a little grace upon the toe. <STAGE>(moving about)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Sir Gregory&mdash;you have been &s;omewhat wanting in politene&s;s to me, but I forgive you.&mdash;Re&s;tored to objects dearer to me than life, I can have no right to complain.</P>
</SP>
<LG>
<L>Surrounded thus with all that life can give</L>
<L>To warm my heart, and make me wi&s;h to live&punc;</L>
<L>Charm'd with the generous friends, who, circled here,</L>
<L>Feel for each pang, and give me tear for tear,</L>
<L>Be it mine to thank them for their tender cares,</L>
<L>And let my future hours be wholly theirs&punc;</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
