<DIV1 TYPE="epilogue">
<PB REF="100">
<HEAD>EPILOGUE.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Spoken by MISS FARREN.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By EDWARD TOPHAM, ESQ.</BYLINE>
<LG>
<L>FIVE di&s;mal acts con&s;um'd in lamentation,</L>
<L>Our Author marries me for Reparation!</L>
<L>&mdash;Well&mdash;tho' we women are, as grey-beards &s;ay,</L>
<L>In duty bound to love and to obey;</L>
<L>And, tho' be&s;et with cares of brats and &s;trife,</L>
<L><HI>Repent</HI> is &s;till the lot of married life;</L>
<L>With le&s;s di&s;may I meet the awful &s;entence,</L>
<L>Since wedlock puts an end to <HI>my</HI> repentance.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>From this bright hour &s;hall gayer &s;cenes ari&s;e,</L>
<L>Such as may charm a female patriot's eyes,</L>
<L>Who&s;e great ambition &s;$ars to nobler plans</L>
<L>Than goat's-beard tippets, or than <HI>Marlbrou$</HI> fans:</L>
<L>Who&s;e ta&s;te the rage for Opera can defy,</L>
<L>And bear to live&mdash;tho' <HI>Pacchierotti</HI> die:</L>
<L>With &s;trange ill-bred indifference can view</L>
<L><HI>VESTRIS</HI> on one leg, or&mdash;<HI>the Dogs</HI> on two.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>But as we women are forbid to roam,</L>
<L>And though we will &s;peak la&s;t&mdash;mu&s;t &s;peak at home&mdash;</L>
<L>To &s;pou&s;e I delegate my vocal powers,</L>
<L>He knows my voice&mdash;and hears it at all hours&mdash;</L>
<L>Thus, $$t in hand, and poiz'd upon one leg,</L>
<L><HI>He'll &s;tart with</HI>&mdash;"Mr. Speaker!&mdash;Sir&mdash;I beg</L>
<L>"One word."&mdash;"Oh, hear him! hear him!&mdash;I defy</L>
<L>"The honourable member in my eye."</L>
<L>Then o'er the Indian plains his forces rally,</L>
<L><HI>Rave about</HI> TIPPOO SAIB <HI>and</HI> HEYDER ALLY;</L>
<L>While I, the member's wife, &s;hall bear a &s;hawl</L>
<L>Given by &s;ome ponderous pr$nce of Leadenhall:</L>
<L>Or, up all night, with fre&s;h impatience wait,</L>
<L>To read next noon the Chronicled debate;</L>
<L>Where, in good &s;tyle, and better words convey'd,</L>
<L>Spou&s;e wonders at the &s;peeches he has made,</L>
<L>And, with the borrow'd grace enamour'd grown,</L>
<L>Stares o'er the tropes and figures&mdash;not his own.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Such is the potent &s;pell that all bewitches&mdash;</L>
<L>"For who would fardels bear,"&mdash;that could make &s;peeches?</L>
<L>"Who brook th' oppre&s;&s;or's wrong&mdash;the proud man's eye,"</L>
<L>When he might ri&s;e again&mdash;with, <HI>I reply?</HI></L>
<L>"Or who would groan beneath life's weary prate,"</L>
<L>Who quietly might &s;leep thro' a debate?</L>
<L>But&mdash;there are charms from oratory flow,</L>
<L>Which tho&s;e who only hear, can never know.</L>
<L>Yet, le&s;t I pre&s;s too long the &s;peaker's art,</L>
<L>Pa&s;s me your vot$ of thanks&mdash;and I depart.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
